detail: Mid 17th century. From accrue + -er, after nouns in the field of legal terminology with the ending -er derived from the infinitive forms of French verbs.
From Arabic, ‘end of the river (i.e. Eridanus)’.
1930s; earliest use found in Eric Partridge (1894–1979), lexicographer and etymologist. Origin unknown.
Late 18th century. From acquire + -or. Compare earlier acquirer.

Late 17th century; earliest use found in Leonard Willan (fl. 1648–1670), writer. From post-classical Latin acquisitor person who acquires something from classical Latin acquīsīt-, past participial stem of acquīrere + -or.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in The Wycliffite Bible (early version). From (i) Anglo-Norman avoutere, avouteire, avouter, avoutour, advouter, advoutoure and Middle French avoutre, also adultere, also adultre, used as both noun and adjective<br>late Middle English; earliest use found in The Wycliffite Bible (early version). From Middle French avoultrer, advoultrer, also Middle French adulterer to commit adultery, to alter, corrupt, falsify and its etymon classical Latin adulterāre to commit adultery (with), to defile by adultery, to mix (a substance) with another, to impair the purity or strength of, to counterfeit, to falsify or tamper with, to corrupt, debase from ad to + alter another.
Early 20th century; earliest use found in Flight International.
Late Middle English (in an earlier sense). From classical Latin Āfer African.
Mid 16th century (in an earlier sense). From affect + -er.
Afrikaans, from South African Dutch Africander, from Dutch Afrikaan ‘an African’ + the personal suffix -der, on the pattern of Hollander ‘Dutchman’.

Early 20th century; earliest use found in The Decatur Review. From Afshar, Avshar (Turkish Avşar, also Afşar, self-designation; Persian Afšār), the name of one of the sub-clans of the Oghuz (Turkic) tribal confederation, now living in south-east Iran.
Old English æfter, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch achter.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in John Trevisa (c1342–?1402), translator. From classical Latin agger material for an earthwork, rubble, offensive earthwork, ramp, defensive earthwork, rampart, road or causeway raised above the level of the surrounding ground, mound or pile of earth or rubble, perhaps from aggerere.
1960s; earliest use found in Life Science. From aggreg- + -ometer.
Late 18th century; earliest use found in New Christian's Magazine. From agonize + -er.
Late 15th century; earliest use found in William Caxton (1415x24–1492), printer, merchant, and diplomat. From aid + -er.
Late 16th century; earliest use found in Anthony Munday (d. 1633), playwright and translator. From aim + -er.
Late Middle English: via Old French from Latin alabaster, alabastrum, from Greek alabastos, alabastros.
Early 17th century: from Spanish alcázar, from Arabic al-qaṣr ‘the castle’.
Old English alor, aler, of Germanic origin; related to German Erle; forms spelled with d are recorded from the 14th century.
Late 16th century: from Spanish el lagarto ‘the lizard’, probably based on Latin lacerta.
Early 20th century; earliest use found in Evening News (London). From allotment + -eer.
Middle English: from Old French aumonier, based on medieval Latin eleemosynarius, from eleemosyna ‘alms’ (see alms).
Early 16th century; earliest use found in Statutes Prohemium Iohannis Rastell. From alnage + -er.
Old English altar, alter, based on late Latin altar, altarium, from Latin altus ‘high’.

Late 19th century; earliest use found in Baedeker's Norway & Sweden. From Swedish alvar, † alfvar from Swedish regional (Öland) alvar, alver, (Gotland) alver, alvar, alvur, related to Swedish alf, alv kind of (hard) subsoil, cognate with Danish al, in the same sense (also Old Danish aluaer), and apparently further with German regional (Bavaria) Alben kind of chalk soil, probably ultimately from the same Indo-European base as classical Latin albus white.
Late Middle English: from French ambassadeur, from Italian ambasciator, based on Latin ambactus ‘servant’.
Late Middle English (also in the sense ‘ambergris’): from Old French ambre, from Arabic ‘anbar ‘ambergris’, later ‘amber’.
Middle English: from Old French ancestre, from Latin antecessor, from antecedere, from ante ‘before’ + cedere ‘go’.

Old English ancor, ancra, via Latin from Greek ankura; reinforced in Middle English by Old French ancre. The current form is from anchora, an erroneous Latin spelling. The verb (from Old French ancrer) dates from Middle English.
Middle English: from Old Norse angr ‘grief’, angra ‘vex’. The original use was in the Old Norse senses; current senses date from late Middle English.
Middle English: as an other until the 16th century.
Old English andswaru (noun), andswarian (verb), of Germanic origin; from a base shared by swear.
Mid 17th century (as antichamber): from French antichambre, from Italian anticamera, from anti- ‘preceding’ + camera (see chamber).
Early 18th century: from French anthère or modern Latin anthera, from Greek anthēra ‘flowery’, from anthos ‘flower’.
Late Middle English (originally denoting the lowest (forward-directed) branch of the antler): from Anglo-Norman French, variant of Old French antoillier, of unknown origin.
Mid 17th century: from Latin applicat- ‘fastened to’ (from the verb applicare) + -or.
Early 20th century: from Latin aqui- (from aqua ‘water’) + -fer ‘bearing’.
Late Middle English: from Latin, ‘judge, supreme ruler’.
Mid 17th century: from French arbre ‘tree, axis’. The spelling change was due to association with Latin arbor ‘tree’.
Middle English: from Old French archier, based on Latin arcus ‘bow’.
Mid 16th century: Latin, literally ‘bearing arms’, from arma ‘arms’ + gerere ‘to bear’.
Mid 18th century; earliest use found in Exmoor Scolding. Representing a variety of regional or colloquial pronunciations of after, after, after.
Late Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French, probably an alteration of Old French artificien, from artifice (see artifice).
Middle English: from Old French aisselier from Latin axilla, diminutive of axis ‘plank’.
Early 17th century (in the sense ‘a star’): via Latin from Greek astēr ‘star’.
Late 17th century: from French, from Old French astelle ‘splinter of wood’, from Latin astula.
Late Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French, variant (used as a noun) of Old French ateindre in the sense ‘convict, bring to justice’ (see attain).
Late 17th century: via Persian from Arabic ‘iṭr ‘perfume, essence’.
Old English nafogār, from nafu (see nave) + gār ‘piercer’. The n was lost by wrong division of a nauger; compare with adder and apron.
Old English. From classical Latin auster the south wind, the south, perhaps from the same Indo-European base as east.

Middle English (in the sense ‘a person who invents or causes something’): from Old French autor, from Latin auctor, from augere ‘increase, originate, promote’. The spelling with th arose in the 15th century, and perhaps became established under the influence of authentic.
1950s; earliest use found in Science News. From auto- + analyser.
From Sanskrit avatāra ‘descent’, from ava ‘down’ + tar- ‘to cross’.
Late Middle English (in the sense ‘declare or confirm to be true’): from Old French averer, based on Latin ad ‘to’ (implying ‘cause to be’) + verus ‘true’.
Early 19th century: named after the town of Axminster in southern England, noted since the 18th century for the production of carpets.
Middle English: from Old French bacheler; of uncertain origin.
Early 16th century: perhaps from badge, with reference to its distinctive head markings. The verb sense (late 18th century) originates from the sport of badger baiting.
1930s: from Balthazar, the name of the king of Babylon, who ‘made a great feast … and drank wine before a thousand’ (Dan. 5:1).

Early 17th century: from French balustre, from Italian balaustro, from balaust(r)a ‘wild pomegranate flower’ (via Latin from Greek balaustion), so named because part of the pillar resembles the curving calyx tube of the flower.
Late 16th century: from French bandoulière; perhaps from Spanish bandolera (from banda ‘sash’), or from Catalan bandolera (from bandoler ‘bandit’).
Mid 17th century: from earlier barrister, alteration of baluster.
Middle English: from Old French baniere, ultimately of Germanic origin and related to band.
Middle English: from Old French barre (noun), barrer (verb), of unknown origin.
Middle English: via Anglo-Norman French from Old French barbe (see barb).
Late Middle English (denoting a palisade or fortification defending an entrance): from Old French barriere, of unknown origin; related to barre.
Late Middle English: from the noun bar, perhaps on the pattern of minister.
Late Middle English: probably from Old French barater ‘deceive’ (see barratry).
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Daily Cleveland (Ohio) Herald. From baseball + -er.
Late 19th century; earliest use found in Wheelman. From baseline + -er.
Late 16th century: from Italian bazarro, from Turkish, from Persian bāzār ‘market’.
Middle English (in the sense ‘large drinking container’): from Old Norse bikarr, perhaps based on Greek bikos ‘drinking bowl’.
Old English beran, of Germanic origin; from an Indo-European root shared by Sanskrit bharati, Greek pherein, and Latin ferre.
Old English beofor, befor, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch bever and German Biber, from an Indo-European root meaning ‘brown’.
Early 17th century (originally a derogatory term for a well-fed servant): the current sense dates from the late 17th century.
Old English bēor, of West Germanic origin, based on monastic Latin biber ‘a drink’, from Latin bibere ‘to drink’; related to Dutch bier and German Bier.
1950s: from the earlier noun beezer, denoting something large or impressive, of unknown origin.
Late Middle English: from Latin, from bene facere ‘do good (to)’ (see benefaction).
From Arabic barbar, from Greek barbaros ‘foreigner’ (see barbarian).
Late 17th century: from be- ‘thoroughly’ + obsolete wilder ‘lead or go astray’, of unknown origin.
From the name of Gottlieb Biedermaier, a fictitious German provincial schoolmaster and poet created by L. Eichrodt (1854).
Old English bēr, of Germanic origin; related to German Bahre, also to bear.
Early 18th century (in the sense ‘having two eyes’): from Latin bini ‘two together’ + oculus ‘eye’, on the pattern of ocular.
1950s; earliest use found in Galaxy Science Fiction.
From the name of John Birch, a USAF officer and ‘first casualty of the Cold War’, killed by Chinese communists in 1945.
Old English biter, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch and German bitter, and probably to bite.
1920s: abbreviation of the phrase bits and pieces.
Old English blǣdre, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch blaar and German Blatter, also to blow.
Late Middle English (as a verb; originally Scots and northern English dialect): from Old Norse blathra ‘talk nonsense’, from blathr ‘nonsense’.
Early 18th century: originally Scots, of imitative origin.
Late 19th century: from blaze + -er. The original general sense was ‘a thing that blazes or shines’ (mid 17th century), giving rise to the term for a brightly coloured sporting jacket.
Middle English: perhaps from Old French blestre ‘swelling, pimple’.
1940s (denoting a huge aerial bomb capable of destroying a whole block of streets): from block + buster.
Old English; earliest use found in Antwerp Glossary. From blood + let + -er, after to let blood.
Mid 16th century; earliest use found in John Daus (c1516–1602), schoolmaster and translator. From blood + thirster.
1926 (originally US, denoting a radio which caused others to bloop, i.e. emit a loud howling noise): from imitative bloop + -er.
Late Middle English (denoting the foaming of the sea, also a bubble on water): perhaps symbolic; compare with blob and blotch.
Middle English: probably of Scandinavian origin and related to blind.
Old English bār, of West Germanic origin; related to Dutch beer and German Bär.
Named after Simón Bolívar (see Bolívar, Simón).
Old English, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch bolster and German Polster.
Mid 16th century (denoting a soldier in charge of a bombard, an early form of cannon): from French, from Old French bombarde ‘cannon’ (see bombard).
1980s: from bonk, on the pattern of blockbuster.
Early 20th century: perhaps an alteration of bonanza.
Early 19th century: probably from the verb boom + -er.
Mid 16th century (in the sense ‘peasant’): from Low German būr or Dutch boer ‘farmer’.
Late Middle English: from Old French bordeure; ultimately of Germanic origin and related to board.

Late 17th century (as a noun in the dialect sense ‘noise, chatter’): of Anglo-Irish origin; probably related to Irish bodhaire ‘noise’, bodhraim ‘deafen, annoy’. The verb (originally dialect) meant ‘confuse with noise’ in the early 18th century.
Early 19th century; earliest use found in Cobbett's Weekly Political Register. From bother + -er.
Late Middle English: shortened from earlier boulderstone.
Late 19th century: from French, originally in the sense ‘person who frequents boulevards’.
1960s: representing a cockney pronunciation of bother.
Old English būr ‘dwelling, inner room’, of Germanic origin; related to German Bauer ‘birdcage’.
1920s: from the name of a company of oil storage engineers.
Early 20th century; earliest use found in The Chicago Tribune. From brainstorm + -er.
Late 17th century: from French brasier, from braise ‘hot coals’.
Early 17th century: from breast and summer.
Old English brǣr, brēr, of unknown origin.
Old English brǣr, brēr, of unknown origin.
Middle English (denoting a retailer or pedlar): from Anglo-Norman French brocour, of unknown ultimate origin.
Old English brōthor, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch broeder and German Bruder, from an Indo-European root shared by Latin frater.
Late 19th century: representing a colloquial pronunciation of brother.
Mid 17th century (originally denoting European hunters in the Caribbean): from French boucanier, from boucan ‘a frame on which to cook or cure meat’, from Tupi mukem.
Middle English: from Old French (escu) bocler, literally ‘(shield) with a boss’, from bocle ‘buckle, boss’ (see buckle).
Mid 19th century: of Aboriginal origin, perhaps an alteration of Kamilaroi gijirrigaa (also in related languages).
Late 16th century: probably from obsolete bug ‘bogey’ (of unknown origin) + bear.

Middle English (originally denoting a heretic, specifically an Albigensian): from Middle Dutch, from Old French bougre ‘heretic’, from medieval Latin Bulgarus ‘Bulgarian’, particularly one belonging to the Orthodox Church and therefore regarded as a heretic by the Roman Church. The sense ‘sodomite’ (16th century) arose from an association of heresy with forbidden sexual practices; its use as a general insult dates from the early 18th century.
Mid 19th century: perhaps from German Bummler, from bummeln ‘stroll, loaf about’.
Mid 16th century (originally Scots, denoting a seat or bench): perhaps related to bunk.
Middle English: from burgh, reinforced by Dutch burger, from burg ‘castle’ (see borough).
Mid 16th century: from legal French burgler or Anglo-Latin burgulator, burglator; related to Old French burgier ‘pillage’.
Late 16th century: from Dutch burgemeester, from burg ‘castle, citadel’ (see borough) + meester ‘master’. The change in the final element was due to association with master.
Late Middle English: from French boursier or (in bursar (sense 1)) medieval Latin bursarius, from bursa ‘bag, purse’ (see bursa).
Early 19th century: perhaps from Dutch bosmeester, from bos ‘bush’ + meester ‘master’.
Mid 17th century; earliest use found in Thomas Urquhart (1611–1660), author and translator. From bustle + -er.
Middle English: from an Anglo-Norman French variant of Old French bochier, from boc ‘he-goat’, probably of the same ultimate origin as buck.
Middle English: from Old French bouteillier ‘cup-bearer’, from bouteille ‘bottle’.
Early 16th century: from Scottish Gaelic cabar ‘pole’.
Late Middle English: from Latin, from cadere ‘to fall’.
Middle English: from Latin Caesar, family name of the Roman statesman Julius Caesar.
Mid 19th century: French; compare with quire.
Middle English: from Old French calendier, from Latin kalendarium ‘account book’, from kalendae (see calends).
Late 15th century (as a verb): from French calendre (noun), calendrer (verb), of unknown origin.
Late 16th century: apparently an alteration of calibre.
Late Middle English: from Old French cambre, dialect variant of chambre ‘arched’, from Latin camurus ‘curved inwards’.
Middle English: from Old French camphore or medieval Latin camphora, from Arabic kāfūr, via Malay from Sanskrit karpūra.
1970s: modern Latin, from Greek kampulos ‘bent’ + bacterium.

Old English, from Latin, ‘crab or creeping ulcer’, translating Greek karkinos, said to have been applied to such tumours because the swollen veins around them resembled the limbs of a crab. canker was the usual form until the 17th century Compare with Cancer.
Late 15th century (denoting a basket): from Latin canistrum, from Greek kanastron ‘wicker basket’, from kanna ‘cane, reed’ (see cane).
Middle English (denoting a tumour): from Old French chancre, from Latin cancer ‘crab’ (see cancer).
Early 18th century (as a verb): short for Canterbury pace or Canterbury gallop, from the supposed easy pace of medieval pilgrims to Canterbury.
Mid 16th century: from Latin, ‘singer’, from canere ‘sing’.
Mid 16th century: from Latin, from capt- ‘seized, taken’, from the verb capere.
Late Middle English (in the general sense ‘wheeled vehicle’): from Old Northern French carre, based on Latin carrum, carrus, of Celtic origin.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in The Mechanics' Magazine. From carbonate + -or.
Mid 19th century: from archaic carburet ‘combine or charge with a hydrocarbon’ + -or.
Mid 16th century (denoting a road or racecourse): from French carrière, from Italian carriera, based on Latin carrus ‘wheeled vehicle’.

Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French, from Old French carpentier, charpentier, from late Latin carpentarius (artifex) ‘carriage (maker)’, from carpentum ‘wagon’, of Gaulish origin; related to car.
Mid 19th century: originally applied to people from the northern states of the US who went to the South after the Civil War to profit from the Reconstruction.
Late 16th century: from Dutch cassier or French caissier, from caisse ‘cash’.
Late 17th century (in castor (sense 2 of the noun)): originally a variant of caster, in the general sense ‘something that casts’.

Late Middle English: perhaps from a variant of Old French chatepelose, literally ‘hairy cat’, influenced by obsolete piller ‘ravager’. The association with ‘cat’ is found in other languages, e.g. Swiss German Teufelskatz (literally ‘devil's cat’), Lombard gatta (literally ‘cat’). Compare with French chaton, English catkin, which resembles a hairy caterpillar.
Mid 17th century: from medieval Latin Cathari (plural), from Greek katharoi ‘the pure’.
Early 17th century: from late Latin, from Greek kathetēr, from kathienai ‘send or let down’.

Late 16th century: from obsolete French chou fleuri ‘flowered cabbage’, probably from Italian cavolfiore or modern Latin cauliflora. The original English form colieflorie or cole-flory had its first element influenced by cole; the second element was influenced by flower during the 17th century.
Mid 16th century: from French, from Italian cavaliere, based on Latin caballus ‘horse’. Compare with caballero and chevalier.
Mid 16th century: from Italian caviale (earlier caviaro) or French caviar, probably from medieval Greek khaviari.
Old English, from Old French cedre or Latin cedrus, from Greek kedros.
Middle English (in the general sense ‘storeroom’): from Old French celier, from late Latin cellarium ‘storehouse’, from Latin cella ‘storeroom or chamber’.
Middle English: from Old French censier, from encensier, from encens (see incense).
Mid 16th century (in censor (sense 2 of the noun)): from Latin, from censere ‘assess’.
Mid 16th century: from Old French cesser ‘cease’, used as a noun.
Early 17th century: from Urdu chādar, chaddar, from Persian čādar ‘sheet or veil’.
Old English ceafor, cefer, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch kever.
Middle English (in the sense ‘trade or trading’): from Old English cēap ‘a bargain’ + faru ‘journey’; probably influenced by Old Norse kaupfǫr.
Middle English (in the sense ‘private room’): from Old French chambre, from Latin camera ‘vault, arched chamber’, from Greek kamara ‘object with an arched cover’.

Mid 16th century (in the sense ‘flute or furrow’): back-formation from chamfering, from French chamfrain, from chant ‘edge’ (see cant) + fraint ‘broken’ (from Old French fraindre ‘break’, from Latin frangere).

Late Old English from Old French cancelier, from late Latin cancellarius ‘porter, secretary’ (originally a court official stationed at the grating separating public from judges), from cancelli ‘crossbars’.
Mid 18th century: from French, from chandelle ‘candle’, from Latin candela, from candere ‘be white, glisten’.
Middle English (denoting a candle maker or candle seller): from Old French chandelier, from chandelle ‘candle’ (see chandelier).
Middle English: from Old French Chantecler, the name of the cock in the fable Reynard the Fox, from chanter ‘sing, crow’ (see chant) + cler ‘clear’.
Middle English: from Old French chapitre, from Latin capitulum, diminutive of caput ‘head’.
Late 17th century: apparently a back-formation from charcoal.

Middle English: from Old French caractere, via Latin from Greek kharaktēr ‘a stamping tool’. From the early sense ‘distinctive mark’ arose ‘token, feature, or trait’ (early 16th century), and from this ‘a description, especially of a person's qualities’, giving rise to ‘distinguishing qualities’.
Middle English: from Old French chartre, from Latin chartula, diminutive of charta ‘paper’ (see card).
Middle English: from Old French chiere ‘face’, from late Latin cara, from Greek kara ‘head’. The original sense was ‘face’, hence ‘expression, mood’, later specifically ‘a good mood’.
Middle English: from exchequer. The original sense ‘chessboard’ gave rise to chequered meaning ‘marked like a chessboard’; hence the sense ‘pattern of squares’ (early 16th century).
Late Middle English (denoting a horseman or mounted knight): from Old French, from medieval Latin caballarius, from Latin caballus ‘horse’. Compare with caballero and cavalier.
Mid 18th century: from French chiffonnier, chiffonnière, literally ‘ragpicker’, also denoting a chest of drawers for odds and ends.
Mid 19th century: perhaps from northern English dialect kipper ‘lively’.
Early 20th century: from chiro- ‘hand’ + Greek praktikos ‘practical’, from prattein ‘do’, + -or.
Middle English: imitative; compare with chatter.
Second World War (originally naval slang): from chock-a-block.

Late Middle English (also denoting diarrhoea): from Old French colere ‘bile, anger’, from Latin cholera ‘diarrhoea’ (from Greek kholera), which in late Latin acquired the senses ‘bile or anger’, from Greek kholē ‘bile’.
Mid 18th century: perhaps from French chaudière ‘stew pot’, related to Old Northern French caudron (see cauldron).
From Urdu caukīdār, from caukī ‘toll house’ + -dār ‘keeper’.

1950s: probably from rhyming slang Chunder Loo ‘spew’, from the name of a cartoon character Chunder Loo of Akim Foo, who appeared in advertisements for Cobra boot polish in the Sydney Bulletin in the early 20th century.
Middle English: from Old French sidre, via ecclesiastical Latin from ecclesiastical Greek sikera, from Hebrew šēḵār ‘strong drink’.
Early 18th century: from French cigare, or from Spanish cigarro, probably from Mayan sik'ar ‘smoking’.

Old English sinder ‘slag’, of Germanic origin; related to German Sinter. The similar but unconnected French cendre (from Latin cinis ‘ashes’) has influenced both the sense development and the spelling. Compare with sinter.
Middle English: from Latin cinnabaris, from Greek kinnabari, of oriental origin.
Late Middle English (in the senses ‘symbol for zero’ and ‘Arabic numeral’): from Old French cifre, based on Arabic ṣifr ‘zero’.
Mid 17th century. From post-classical Latin citator person who cites or quotes from classical Latin citāt-, past participial stem of citāre + -or.
Late 16th century; earliest use found in Thomas Lupton (fl. 1572–1584), political and religious controversialist. From cite + -er.

Mid 19th century; earliest use found in William T. Brande (1788–1866), chemist. From classific- + -ator. Compare French classificateur, Italian classificatore, both in sense ‘person who classifies objects, author of classifications’.
Old English (as a verb), of imitative origin.
Early 18th century: from German Klavier, from French clavier, from medieval Latin claviarius ‘key bearer’, from Latin clavis ‘key’.
Middle English: from Old French cler, from Latin clarus.
1930s: from early film serials in which episodes ended with characters in desperate situations such as hanging off the edge of a cliff.
Mid 17th century: from obsolete Dutch klinckaerd (earlier form of klinker), from klinken ‘to clink’.
Early 19th century: from Greek klinein ‘to slope’ + -meter.
Second World War (apparently air force slang): of unknown origin.
Middle English (in the sense ‘place of religious seclusion’): from Old French cloistre, from Latin claustrum, clostrum ‘lock, enclosed place’, from claudere, ‘to close’.
Middle English clother, from cloth. The change in the ending was due to association with -ier.
Old English clāfre, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch klaver and German Klee.
Old English clyster; probably related to clot.
Late Middle English: variant of dialect clotter ‘to clot’, influenced by cluster and clatter.
Late Middle English: via Old French from late Latin coadjutor, from co- (from Latin cum ‘together with’) + adjutor ‘assistant’ (from adjuvare ‘to help’).
Late 19th century: perhaps related to English dialect cob ‘take a liking to’.
Early 18th century: from cock (expressing size or vigour) + chafer.
Early 19th century: from cock + -er (the dog was bred to flush out game birds such as woodcock).
Mid 18th century: perhaps a variant of cadger (see cadge).
Middle English: from Old French coffre ‘chest’, via Latin from Greek kophinos ‘basket’.
Middle English: based on Latin colare ‘to strain’.
Middle English: from Old French colier, from Latin collare ‘band for the neck, collar’, from collum ‘neck’.

Middle English: from coal + -ier. The original sense was ‘maker of charcoal’, who usually brought it to market, hence ‘person selling charcoal’, later ‘person selling coal’, whence the current senses.
Mid 16th century (in an earlier sense). From colour + -er.
Early 20th century (Russian Revolution): from Russian komissar, from French commissaire, from medieval Latin commissarius (see commissary).
Middle English (denoting a citizen or burgess): from medieval Latin communarius, from communa, communia ‘community’, based on Latin communis (see common).
Late 19th century: from Latin comparat- ‘paired, matched’, from the verb comparare (see compare), + -or.

Early 17th century (denoting a local person employed in a European household in SE Asia or India to make small purchases and keep the household accounts): from Portuguese, ‘buyer’, from late Latin comparator, from Latin comparare ‘to purchase’, from com- ‘with’ + parare ‘provide’.
Late 15th century: variant of controller, by erroneous association with French compte ‘calculation’ or its source, late Latin computus.
Mid 16th century: medieval Latin, from Latin com- ‘together with’ + purgator, from purgare ‘purify’ (see compurgation).
Mid 17th century; earliest use found in John Ogilby (1600–1676), publisher and geographer. From compute + -or.
Late 17th century: from medieval Latin consiliarius ‘counsellor’, from Latin concilium (see council).
Early 17th century: from Spanish cóndor, from Quechua kuntur.
Latin, ‘I confess’, from the formula Confiteor Deo Omnipotenti ‘I confess to Almighty God’.
1960s: blend of conformational (see conformation) and isomer.
Mid 18th century: from Latin, from con- ‘together with’ + genus, gener- ‘race, stock’.
Middle English: from Old French congre, via Latin from Greek gongros.
Mid 19th century: from Latin, literally ‘cone-bearing’, from conus (see cone).

Mid 19th century (a dialect word denoting a snail shell, with which the game, or a form of it, was originally played): perhaps from conch, but associated with (and frequently spelled) conquer in the 19th and early 20th centuries: an alternative name was conquerors.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in Reginald Pecock (c1392–?1459), bishop of Chichester and religious author. From conserve + -er. Compare Middle French conserveur person or thing that conserves.
Middle English cowper, from Middle Dutch, Middle Low German kūper, from kūpe ‘tub, vat’, based on Latin cupa. Compare with coop.
Late Middle English: from co- ‘together’ + parcener.
Mid 16th century: from Middle English cope ‘buy’, from Dutch, Low German kōpen; related to German kaufen, also to cheap.
Old English copor, coper (related to Dutch koper and German Kupfer), based on late Latin cuprum, from Latin cyprium aes ‘Cyprus metal’ (so named because Cyprus was the chief source).
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French cordewaner, from Old French cordewan, ‘of Cordoba’ (see cordovan).
Middle English: from Old French coriandre, from Latin coriandrum, from Greek koriannon.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French, based on Latin cornu ‘horn, tip, corner’.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French coruner, from corune ‘a crown’ (see crown); reflecting the Latin title custos placitorum coronae ‘guardian of the pleas of the Crown’.

Late 16th century (as a military term denoting a strip of land along the outer edge of a ditch, protected by a parapet): from French, from Italian corridore, alteration (by association with corridore ‘runner’) of corridoio ‘running place’, from correre ‘to run’, from Latin currere. The current sense dates from the early 19th century.
Early 16th century (denoting an apple seller): from Costard + -monger.
Mid 19th century: French, from costumer ‘dress in a costume’ (see costume).
Mid 18th century: modern Latin, from Latin cotoneum (see quince) + -aster.
Late 18th century: from French couguar, abbreviation of modern Latin cuguarcarana, from Guarani guaçuarana.
Old English, from Latin culter ‘knife or ploughshare’.
Late Middle English: alteration of counsellor, by association with council.
Late Middle English: from French contre-teneur, from obsolete Italian contratenore, based on Latin tenor (see tenor).

Late Middle English (denoting a person sent to run with a message): originally from Old French coreor; later from French courier (now courrier), from Italian corriere; based on Latin currere ‘to run’.
Middle English: from Old French corsier, based on Latin cursus (see course).
Middle English: via Anglo-Norman French from Old French cortoyer ‘be present at court’, from cort (see court).
Middle English: from Old French covrir, from Latin cooperire, from co- (expressing intensive force) + operire ‘to cover’. The noun is partly a variant of covert.
Early 17th century (denoting the hollow forming the mouth of a volcano): via Latin from Greek kratēr ‘mixing-bowl’, from krasis ‘mixture’.
Late 17th century: from Greek kremastēr, from krema- ‘hang’.

Early 18th century (denoting a person standing behind a gambler to give advice): French, from Old French cropier ‘pillion rider, rider on the croup’, related to Old French croupe (see croup). Compare with crupper.

Middle English; earliest use found in Subsidy Roll, Leicestershire. Alteration of coroner, after crown<br>late Middle English; earliest use found in Promptorium Parvulorum. Partly from crown + -er<br>early 17th century; earliest use found in Diurnal of Remarkable Occurrents. Alteration of colonel, after crown.

Middle English (originally denoting the person who carried a processional cross in front of an archbishop): partly from Old French croisier ‘cross-bearer’, from crois ‘cross’, based on Latin crux; reinforced by Old French crocier ‘bearer of a bishop's crook’, from croce (see crosse).
Mid 16th century: from Christian Latin, from Latin crux, cruc- ‘cross’.
Middle English: from Old French cropiere, related to croupe (see croup). Compare with croupier.
Early 17th century; earliest use found in Cyril Tourneur (d. 1626), writer and soldier. From crystallize + -er.
Late Middle English: from Old French cocombre, coucombre, from Latin cucumis, cucumer-.
Mid 16th century: French, from cuirasse, from Old French cuirace (see cuirass).
Middle English (in the sense ‘overthrow, destroy’): probably from encumber.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in Acts of Parliament of Scotland. From Anglo-Norman coninger, conyngere, conyngair, coniger, coningere, coninggre, cuninger, conier, conyer from coninge, couning, conig, coni + -er, -air.

Late Middle English (denoting an ecclesiastical pastor, also (still a Scots legal term) the guardian of a minor): from Old French curateur or, in later use, directly from Latin curator, from curare (see cure). The current sense dates from the mid 17th century.
Middle English (denoting a runner or running messenger): from Latin, ‘runner’, from curs- (see cursive). cursor (sense 2 of the noun) dates from the late 16th century.
Early 16th century. From classical Latin custōdia custody + -er.
Middle English: from Old French coutelier, from coutel ‘knife’, from Latin cultellus, diminutive of culter ‘knife, ploughshare’. Compare with coulter.
Late 19th century; earliest use found in Milwaukee (Wisconsin) Observer. Either from cycle + -er, or shortened from bicycler.
Late 16th century: from Latin cylindrus, from Greek kulindros ‘roller’, from kulindein ‘to roll’.
Late Middle English: perhaps from obsolete dag ‘pierce, stab’, influenced by Old French dague ‘long dagger’.
Mid 19th century (originally US): of unknown origin.
Middle English (in the sense ‘jurisdiction or power’, specifically ‘power to harm’): from Old French dangier, based on Latin dominus ‘lord’.
Late Middle English: probably from a Middle Low German or Middle Dutch word meaning ‘strong, stout’.
Old English dohtor, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch dochter and German Tochter, from an Indo-European root shared by Greek thugatēr.
Old English dēore, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch dier ‘beloved’, also to Dutch duur and German teuer ‘expensive’.
Late Middle English: from French débarrer, from Old French desbarrer ‘unbar’, from des- (expressing reversal) + barrer ‘to bar’.
1940s; earliest use found in Journal of the American Chemical Society.
Middle English: from Latin, from decem ‘ten’ (being originally the tenth month of the Roman year).
Late 19th century: from French décor, from the verb décorer, from Latin decorare ‘embellish’ (see decorate).
Late 19th century: probably a corruption of denarius.
Old English dēor, also originally denoting any quadruped, used in the (now archaic) phrase small deer meaning ‘small creatures collectively’; of Germanic origin; related to Dutch dier, German Tier.
Turkish, from Persian daftardār, from daftar ‘register’ + -dār ‘holder’.
Based on Latin denarius; compare with dinar.
1970s; earliest use found in Phi Delta Kappan. From deschool + -er.
Middle English: from Old French, based on Latin dextera ‘the right hand’, from dexter ‘on the right’ (because the squire led the knight's horse with his right hand).
Early 17th century: from Anglo-Norman French detener ‘detain’ (used as a noun), variant of Old French detenir (see detain).
Mid 18th century: modern Latin, from Latin detrus- ‘thrust down’, from the verb detrudere.
Late 19th century: named after Sir James Dewar (see Dewar, Sir James).
Mid 16th century: from Latin, ‘on the right’.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Thomas Graham (1805–1869), chemist. From dialyse + -er.
Late Middle English: from Old French diametre, via Latin from Greek diametros (grammē) ‘(line) measuring across’, from dia ‘across’ + metron ‘measure’.

Middle English: from Old French diapre, from medieval Latin diasprum, from medieval Greek diaspros (adjective), from dia ‘across’ + aspros ‘white’. The term seems originally to have denoted a costly fabric, but after the 15th century it was used as in diaper (sense 2 of the noun); babies' nappies were originally made from pieces of this fabric, hence diaper (sense 1 of the noun) (late 16th century).
Early 19th century (originally US): perhaps from obsolete dicker ‘set of ten (hides’), used as a unit of trade, based on Latin decem ‘ten’.
1930s: from di- ‘two’, on the pattern of polymer.
From Arabic and Persian dīnār, Turkish and Serbian dinar, via late Greek from Latin denarius (see denarius).
Mid 16th century: from Italian disastro ‘ill-starred event’, from dis- (expressing negation) + astro ‘star’ (from Latin astrum).
Mid 16th century (in disbar (sense 2)): from dis- ‘away’ + bar.
Early 17th century: from French désenterrer, from dis- (expressing reversal) + enterrer ‘to inter’.
Late 15th century (as a verb): alteration, influenced by order, of earlier disordain, from Old French desordener, ultimately based on Latin ordinare ‘ordain’.

Mid 16th century (originally in the sense ‘bad temper’, later ‘illness’): from Middle English distemper ‘upset, derange’, from late Latin distemperare ‘soak, mix in the wrong proportions’, from dis- ‘thoroughly’ + temperare ‘mingle’. Compare with temper. distemper (sense 1) dates from the mid 18th century.
Mid 17th century (in the dialect sense ‘tremble, quiver’): variant of dialect didder; related to dodder.
Late Middle English: from French diviseur or Latin divisor, from dividere (see divide).
Middle English (in the senses ‘learned person’ and ‘Doctor of the Church’): via Old French from Latin doctor ‘teacher’ (from docere ‘teach’).
Early 17th century: variant of obsolete dialect dadder; related to dither.

From early Flemish or Low German daler, from German T(h)aler, short for Joachimsthaler, a coin from the silver mine of Joachimsthal ( ‘Joachim's valley’), now Jáchymov in the Czech Republic. The term was later applied to a coin used in the Spanish-American colonies, which was also widely used in the British North American colonies at the time of the American War of Independence, hence adopted as the name of the US monetary unit in the late 18th century.
Middle English: from Old French doneur, from Latin donator, from donare ‘give’.
1930s: perhaps an alteration of do for in phrases like that will do for now.
Old English duru, dor, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch deur ‘door’ and German Tür ‘door’, Tor ‘gate’; from an Indo-European root shared by Latin foris ‘gate’ and Greek thura ‘door’.
Old English (denoting a bee or buzzing fly), probably imitative.
Late 16th century (denoting the window of a dormitory or bedroom): from Old French dormeor ‘dormitory’, from dormir ‘to sleep’.
Late 19th century: from French, denoting a bundle of papers with a label on the back, from dos ‘back’, based on Latin dorsum.
Mid 16th century: from Old French douagiere, from douage ‘dower’, from douer ‘endow’, from Latin dotare ‘endow’ (see dower).
Late Middle English: from Old French douaire, from medieval Latin dotarium, from Latin dotare ‘endow’, from dos, dot- ‘dowry’; related to dare ‘give’.
Late Middle English (denoting a maker of woollen cloth): from Old French drapier, from drap ‘cloth’, from late Latin drappus.
Early 17th century; earliest use found in Thomas Middleton (d. 1627), playwright. From drug + -ster.
Middle English (in the sense ‘person who dries’): from the verb dry + -er.

Mid 18th century; earliest use found in Whitehall Evening Post. From dud + -er<br>mid 17th century; earliest use found in William Rowley (?1585–1626), actor and playwright. Apparently a variant of didder.
Mid 18th century; earliest use found in Thomas Warton (1728–1790), poet and historian. From Old Icelandic dvergar, plural of dvergr dwarf.
Mid 19th century: from Scots dowfart ‘stupid person’, from douf ‘spiritless’.
Late 18th century: from South African Dutch, from Dutch, literally ‘diver’, from the antelope's habit of plunging through bushes when pursued; related to duck.
Late 15th century: from Old French doulcemer, probably from Latin dulce melos ‘sweet melody’.
1930s: originally Dempster Dumpster, trade name (based on dump) given by the American manufacturers, Dempster Brothers of Knoxville, Tennessee.
Early 19th century: from French dynamomètre, from Greek dunamis ‘power’ + French -mètre ‘(instrument) measuring’.
Old English ēare, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch oor and German Ohr, from an Indo-European root shared by Latin auris and Greek ous.
Old English ēastre; of Germanic origin and related to German Ostern and east; perhaps from Ēastre, the name of a goddess associated with spring.
1960s; earliest use found in Alan Sillitoe (1928–2010), novelist. From eff + -er.
Early 18th century: probably from egg (from the shape of the caterpillar's cocoon) + -er.
Late 17th century: from Icelandic æthur, from Old Norse æthr.
Old English ǣgther, contracted form of ǣg(e)hwæther, of Germanic origin; ultimately related to aye and whether.
Old English ieldra, eldra, of Germanic origin; related to German älter, also to eld and old.
Early 19th century. From electro- + motor, after French électromoteur.
1930s: the name of a tributary of the River Elbe in Germany.
Mid 17th century: variant of dialect eel-fare ‘the passage of young eels up a river’, also ‘a brood of young eels’, from eel + fare in its original sense ‘a journey’.
Old English ǣmyrge, of Germanic origin; related to Old High German eimuria ‘pyre’, Danish emmer, Swedish mörja ‘embers’. The b was added in English for ease of pronunciation.
Late Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French enbrouder, from en- ‘in, on’ + Old French brouder, broisder ‘decorate with embroidery’, of Germanic origin.

Middle English (especially representing the title given to the head of the Roman Empire): from Old French emperere, from Latin imperator ‘military commander’, from imperare ‘to command’, from in- ‘towards’ + parare ‘prepare, contrive’.
Late 19th century: Latin, from emere ‘to buy’.

Middle English (in the senses ‘meet as an adversary’ and ‘a meeting of adversaries’; formerly also as incounter): from Old French encontrer (verb), encontre (noun), based on Latin in- ‘in’ + contra ‘against’.
Middle English (in the sense ‘cause trouble to, entangle’; formerly also as incumber): from Old French encombrer ‘block up’, from en- ‘in’ + combre ‘river barrage’.
Middle English (formerly also as ingender): from Old French engendrer, from Latin ingenerare, from in- ‘in’ + generare ‘beget’ (see generate).
Mid 17th century. Partly from English + -er, and partly from English + -er.
From Greek ephoros ‘overseer’, from epi ‘above’ + the base of horan ‘see’.
Early 20th century (originally US, as a trade name): from escalade ‘climb a wall by ladder’ (from escalade), on the pattern of elevator.
Late Middle English: from French eschare or late Latin eschara ‘scar or scab’, from Greek (see also scar).
Mid 17th century: from French, from Italian spalliera, from spalla ‘shoulder’, from Latin spatula (see spatula), in late Latin ‘shoulder blade’.
Mid 19th century: from German, probably from a blend of Essig ‘vinegar’ and Äther ‘ether’.

Late Middle English: from Old French, or via Latin from Greek aithēr ‘upper air’, from the base of aithein ‘burn, shine’. Originally the word denoted a substance believed to occupy space beyond the sphere of the moon. ether (sense 3) arose in the mid 17th century and ether (sense 1) in the mid 18th century.
1970s: from event, in three-day event (see eventing).
Old English ǣfre, of unknown origin.
Late Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French, variant of Old French aiguiere, based on Latin aquarius ‘of water’, from aqua ‘water’.

Late 15th century; earliest use found in William Caxton (1415x24–1492), printer, merchant, and diplomat. From post-classical Latin examinator investigator, explorer (early 3rd cent. in Tertullian), judge, academic examiner, assayer from classical Latin exāmināt-, past participial stem of exāmināre + -or.
Late 18th century (as an exclamation): from Latin, comparative of excelsus, from ex- ‘out, beyond’ + celsus ‘lofty’.

Middle English: from Old French eschequier, from medieval Latin scaccarium ‘chessboard’, from scaccus (see check). The original sense was ‘chessboard’. Current senses derive from the Norman department of state dealing with the royal revenues, named Exchequer from the chequered tablecloth on which accounts were kept by means of counters. The spelling was influenced by Latin ex- ‘out’ (see ex). Compare with chequer.
Late Middle English: from Old French exemplaire, from late Latin exemplarium, from Latin exemplum ‘sample, imitation’ (see example).
Mid 16th century (in an earlier sense). From exemplify + -er.
Middle English: via Old French or late Latin, from Latin exposit- ‘exposed, explained’, from exponere (see expound).
Early 16th century: from Latin, comparative of exter ‘outer’.
Early 17th century; earliest use found in Randle Cotgrave (fl. 1587–?1630), lexicographer. From eye + -er.
Late Middle English (meaning ‘doer’, also in the Scots sense ‘agent’): from French facteur or Latin factor, from fact- ‘done’, from the verb facere.
Late Middle English (in the senses ‘stammer’ and ‘stagger’): perhaps from the verb fold (which was occasionally used of the faltering of the legs or tongue) + -ter as in totter.
Middle English (in the sense ‘intimate’, ‘on a family footing’): from Old French familier, from Latin familiaris, from familia ‘household servants, family’, from famulus ‘servant’.
Mid 16th century: from Old French ferrier, from Latin ferrarius, from ferrum ‘iron, horseshoe’.
Old English fæder, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch vader and German Vater, from an Indo-European root shared by Latin pater and Greek patēr.
Old English fǣr ‘calamity, danger’, fǣran ‘frighten’, also ‘revere’, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch gevaar and German Gefahr ‘danger’.
Old English fether, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch veer and German Feder, from an Indo-European root shared by Sanskrit patra ‘wing’, Latin penna ‘feather’, and Greek pteron, pterux ‘wing’.
Late 17th century; earliest use found in Isaac Chauncy (1632–1712), Independent minister. From federate + -or.
Mid 18th century: alteration of German Feldspat, Feldspath, from Feld ‘field’ + Spat, Spath ‘spar’ (see spar). The form felspar is by mistaken association with German Fels ‘rock’.
Late Middle English: from the rare word fester ‘fistula’, later ‘festering sore’, or Old French festrir (verb), both from Old French festre (noun), from Latin fistula ‘pipe, reed, fistula’.
Late 15th century: from Latin, from fetere ‘to stink’. Compare with fetid.
Old English feter, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch veter ‘a lace’, from an Indo-European root shared by foot.
Old English fēfor, from Latin febris; reinforced in Middle English by Old French fievre, also from febris.

Late 18th century: from French flibustier, first applied to pirates who pillaged the Spanish colonies in the West Indies. In the mid 19th century (via Spanish filibustero), the term denoted American adventurers who incited revolution in several Latin American states, whence filibuster (sense 2 of the noun). The verb was used to describe tactics intended to sabotage US congressional proceedings, whence filibuster (sense 1 of the noun).
Early 20th century; earliest use found in Moving Picture World. From film + -er.
Late Middle English (denoting a piece of felt): from French filtre, from medieval Latin filtrum ‘felt used as a filter’, of West Germanic origin and related to felt.
Early 17th century: from French, from finance (see finance).
Old English, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch vinger and German Finger.
Late 19th century (originally in the sense ‘teenage girl’): perhaps from the noun flap in the dialect sense ‘newly fledged wild duck or partridge’ (or ‘woman of loose character’).
Middle English: from Old French flechier, from fleche ‘arrow’.
Old English flicorian, flycerian ‘to flutter’, probably of Germanic origin and related to Low German flickern and Dutch flikkeren.
Late Middle English: frequentative of flit.
Old English flōr, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch vloer and German Flur.
Late 16th century: perhaps a blend of founder and blunder, or perhaps symbolic, fl- frequently beginning words connected with swift or sudden movement.

Middle English flour, from Old French flour, flor, from Latin flos, flor-. The original spelling was no longer in use by the late 17th century except in its specialized sense ‘ground grain’ (see flour).
Late 18th century: from fluor ‘a flow, a mineral used as a flux, fluorspar’ (from Latin fluor, from fluere ‘to flow’) + spar.
Early 17th century (in the sense ‘make slightly drunk’): perhaps of Scandinavian origin and related to Icelandic flaustra ‘hurry, bustle’.
Old English floterian, flotorian, a frequentative form related to fleet.
Old English fōdor, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch voeder and German Futter, also to food.
Late 19th century: from modern Latin foliaris, from Latin folium ‘leaf’.
Old English, probably a reduction of a Germanic preposition meaning ‘before’ (in place or time); related to German für, also to fore.
Mid 19th century: from Latin foramen, foramin- (see foramen) + -fer ‘bearing’ (from ferre ‘to bear’).
Old English forberan (see for-, bear). The original senses were ‘endure, bear with’, hence ‘endure the absence of, do without’, also ‘control oneself’, hence ‘refrain from’ ( Middle English).
Late 15th century: from fore + bear, variant of obsolete beer ‘someone who exists’ (from be + -er).
Middle English: from Old French forestier, from forest (see forest).
Middle English: from Old English forma (see foremost) + -er.
Late 18th century (denoting the centre of attention or activity): from French, ‘hearth, home’, based on Latin focus ‘domestic hearth’.
Middle English: from Old French fraitur, shortening of refreitor, from late Latin refectorium ‘refectory’.
Late 16th century: from Dutch vrijbuiter, from vrij ‘free’ + buit ‘booty’, + the noun suffix -er. Compare with filibuster.
Middle English: from Old French frere, from Latin frater ‘brother’.
Early 18th century: based on obsolete fitter ‘break into fragments, shred’; perhaps related to German Fetzen ‘rag, scrap’.
Late Middle English: from Old French frontiere, based on Latin frons, front- ‘front’.
Middle English (in the sense ‘fruit grower’): from Old French fruitier, from fruit ‘fruit’; in later use from fruit + -er. The current sense dates from the 19th century.
From German Führer ‘leader’, part of the title Führer und Reichskanzler ‘Leader and Chancellor of the Empire’ assumed in 1934 by Adolf Hitler, Adolf.
Late 17th century: from Hebridean Norn dialect, from Old Norse fúll ‘stinking, foul’ (because of its habit of regurgitating its stomach contents when disturbed) + már ‘gull’.
1930s: from function, on the pattern of words such as factor.
Mid 17th century (in the sense ‘of or like a cord or thread’): from Latin funiculus (diminutive of funis ‘rope’) + -ar.
Middle English: from Old French forreor, from forrer ‘to line, sheathe’ (see fur). The change in the ending in the 16th century was due to association with -ier.
Late 17th century: from French, from fusil (see fusil).
Late 16th century (in gaffer (sense 3 of the noun)): probably a contraction of godfather; compare with gammer.
Early 18th century: from French guêtre, probably of Germanic origin and related to wrist.
Early 19th century: from Malay gambir, the name of the plant.
Old English gandra, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch gander, also to gannet.
Middle English: from Old French gartier, from garet ‘bend of the knee, calf of the leg’, probably of Celtic origin.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Journal of the Society of Arts. From gasify + -er.
Late 18th century (in the sense ‘container for holding or measuring a gas’): from French gazomètre, from gaz ‘gas’ + -mètre ‘(instrument) measuring’.
Old English gaderian, of West Germanic origin; related to Dutch gaderen, also to together.

Early 17th century (in the sense ‘journalist’): via French from Italian gazzettiere, from gazzetta (see gazette). The current sense comes from a late 17th-century gazetteer called The Gazetteer's: or, Newsman's Interpreter: Being a Geographical Index.

Middle English: of Scandinavian origin; compare with Old Norse gervi. Early senses expressed the general meaning ‘equipment or apparatus’, later ‘mechanism’: hence gear (sense 1 of the noun) (early 19th century).
Late 19th century: representing a dialect pronunciation of earlier guiser ‘mummer’.

Late Middle English: from Old French gendre (modern genre), based on Latin genus ‘birth, family, nation’. The earliest meanings were ‘kind, sort, genus’ and ‘type or class of noun, etc.’ (which was also a sense of Latin genus).
Early 18th century: from Dutch, from Old French genevre, from an alteration of Latin juniperus (gin being flavoured with juniper berries). The variant spelling is due to association with Geneva.
Late Middle English (in the sense ‘father’): from Old French geniteur or Latin genitor, from the root of gignere ‘beget’. The current sense dates from the mid 20th century.
Late Middle English: from late Latin geometra, based on Greek geōmetrēs, from gē ‘earth’ + metrēs ‘measurer’.

Late Middle English: from medieval Latin germandra, based on Greek khamaidrus, literally ‘ground oak’, from khamai ‘on the ground’ + drus ‘oak’ (because the leaves of some species were thought to resemble those of the oak).

Early 19th century: from the name of Governor Elbridge Gerry of Massachusetts + salamander, from the supposed similarity between a salamander and the shape of a new voting district on a map drawn when he was in office (1812), the creation of which was felt to favour his party; the map (with claws, wings, and fangs added) was published in the Boston Weekly Messenger, with the title The Gerry-Mander.
Late 18th century: from Icelandic Geysir, the name of a particular spring in Iceland; related to geysa ‘to gush’.

Middle English gilofre (in the sense ‘clove’), from Old French gilofre, girofle, via medieval Latin from Greek karuophullon (from karuon ‘nut’ + phullon ‘leaf’). The ending was altered by association with flower, but gilliver survived in dialect.
Late Middle English: from Old Norse gymbr, of unknown ultimate origin.
Late Old English gingifer, conflated in Middle English with Old French gingimbre, from medieval Latin gingiber, from Greek zingiberis, from Pali siṅgivera, of Dravidian origin.
Early 17th century: from gird in the archaic sense ‘brace, strengthen’.
Mid 18th century: from French, from glace ‘ice’, based on Latin glacies.
Late Middle English: from Latin, from gladius ‘sword’.
Late Middle English: probably of Scandinavian origin; related to Swedish glimra and Danish glimre.
Late Middle English: probably from Middle Low German glistern or Middle Dutch glisteren.
Late Middle English: from Old Norse glitra.
Late Middle English: from medieval Latin, from glossare, from Latin glossa (see gloss).
Late 15th century: perhaps a Scots variant of synonymous dialect glore, or from obsolete glow ‘to stare’, both possibly of Scandinavian origin.
Late 19th century; earliest use found in Evening News (London). From goal + -er.
Early 17th century: so named because the bird was thought to suck goats' udders.
1960s: from go for (i.e. go and fetch).
1960s: origin uncertain; sense 1 perhaps from Gomer Pyle, a US television character portrayed as an ignorant hillbilly; sense 2 perhaps an acronym from get out of my emergency room.
Early 17th century: via French from Italian gondoliere, from gondola (see gondola).
Mid 18th century: from French goniomètre, from Greek gōnia ‘angle’ + French -mètre ‘(instrument) measuring’.
Late 19th century: from an earlier sense ‘peanut’, from Kikongo nguba.
Early 17th century: probably from goose + -ander as in dialect bergander ‘shelduck’ (the colouring of the male goosander resembling that of the shelduck).
Late 18th century: perhaps from Canadian French gaufre ‘honeycomb’ (because the gopher ‘honeycombs’ the ground with its burrows).
Middle English: apparently from goose + summer, perhaps from the time of year around St Martin's summer, i.e. early November, when geese were eaten (gossamer being common then).
Late Middle English: from Old French gramaire, via Latin from Greek grammatikē (tekhnē) ‘(art) of letters’, from gramma, grammat- ‘letter of the alphabet, thing written’.
Late 19th century: named after William Greener (1806–69) or his son William W. Greener, gunsmiths and authors.
Late 17th century: from French, from grenade (see grenade).
1960s: origin uncertain; perhaps a humorous representation of an upper-class pronunciation of grouser ‘grouse-shooter’.
Middle English (originally ‘a person who sold things in the gross’ (i.e. in large quantities)): from Old French grossier, from medieval Latin grossarius, from late Latin grossus ‘gross’.
Early 17th century: from Portuguese garoupa, probably from a local term in South America.
Late 15th century: from the archaic verb guise ‘dress fantastically’, from the noun guise.
Early 17th century: from Spanish guitarra (partly via French), from Greek kithara, denoting an instrument similar to the lyre.
Late 18th century: named after E. Gunter (see Gunter's chain).
Late 17th century: perhaps from Old Norse hárr ‘hoar, hoary’.

Middle English: probably based on Anglo-Norman French hapertas, perhaps the name of a fabric, of unknown origin. In early use the term denoted a dealer in a variety of household goods, later also specifically a hatter. Current senses date from the early 17th century.
Early 16th century. Apparently from hackbut (although this is first attested slightly later) + -er.
Late 16th century; earliest use found in Edward Hake (fl. 1564–1604), lawyer and satirist. From hack + -ster.
Early 16th century: from French hallebardier, from hallebarde (see halberd).
From Czech haléř, from Middle High German haller, from Schwäbisch Hall, a town in Germany where coins were minted.
Old English hælftre, of Germanic origin, meaning ‘something to hold things by’; related to German Halfter, also to helve.
Late 19th century (originally US): from German, from Hamburg.
Old English hamor, hamer, of Germanic origin: related to Dutch hamer, German Hammer, and Old Norse hamarr ‘rock’. The original sense was probably ‘stone tool’.
Middle English (denoting any large case or casket): from Anglo-Norman French hanaper ‘case for a goblet’, from Old French hanap ‘goblet’, of Germanic origin.
Early 17th century: from German, from Old High German hamustro ‘corn weevil’.
Late 17th century; earliest use found in The London Gazette. From hand + -er.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Harriet Martineau (1802–1876), writer and journalist. From hand + shaker, after to shake hands.
Late 15th century; earliest use found in Table Prouffytable Lernynge. From hand + worker, perhaps after Middle Dutch hantwerker (Dutch handwerker).
Late 17th century (in the sense ‘shelter’): from French; probably from Germanic bases meaning ‘hamlet’ and ‘enclosure’.
Early 17th century: probably related to hang; compare with Dutch hunkeren.

Middle English: from Old French herbergere, from herbergier ‘provide lodging for’, from herberge ‘lodging’, from Old Saxon heriberga ‘shelter for an army, lodging’ (from heri ‘army’ + a Germanic base meaning ‘fortified place’), related to harbour. The term originally denoted a person who provided lodging, later one who went ahead to find lodgings for an army or for a nobleman and his retinue, hence, a herald (mid 16th century).
Mid 19th century (in an earlier sense). From Hardanger, the name of a district in western Norway, where the violin and embroidery were originally made.
Mid 16th century; earliest use found in Roger Hutchinson (d. 1555), religious writer. From hatch + -er.
Late Middle English. From hat + maker.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French haucer, from Old French haucier ‘to hoist’, based on Latin altus ‘high’.

Old English hadre, hedre (recorded in place names), of unknown origin. The word was chiefly Scots until the 16th century; the change in the first syllable in the 18th century was due to association with heath.
Old English heahfore, of unknown origin.
1980s. From scientific Latin Helicobacter, genus name from ancient Greek ἑλικο- + -bacter.
Late 19th century: from French hélicoptère, from Greek helix ‘spiral’ + pteron ‘wing’.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Washington Irving (1783–1859), author.
From German Heller, earlier haller (see haler).
1940s; earliest use found in Journal of the American Chemical Society.
Old English hire, genitive and dative of hīo, hēo ‘she’.
Late Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French heriter, based on Latin hereditarius (see hereditary). The spelling change in the 16th century was by association with words ending in -or.
Late Middle English: from Latin, from Greek hexametros ‘of six measures’ (from hex ‘six’ + metron ‘measure’).
1930s (in sense ‘female jazz dancer’, then ‘fashionable person in the jazz world’): from hip + -ster.
Old English hār, of Germanic origin; related to German hehr ‘majestic, noble’.
Late 17th century (as a verb): variant of the rare verb hollo; related to halloo.
Mid 17th century: corresponding to and contemporary with Dutch holster, of unknown origin.
Late Middle English; earliest use found in Geoffrey Chaucer (c1340–1400), poet and administrator. Partly from homage + -er, and partly from Anglo-Norman homager person who owes homage.
Mid 16th century; earliest use found in John Palsgrave (d. 1554), teacher and scholar of languages. From home + comer.
Late 18th century; earliest use found in The London Magazine. Partly from hone + -er, and partly (in later use) from hone + -er.
Representing a regional pronunciation of whore.
1920s: named after W. H. Hoover (see Hoover, William).
Middle English: via Old French from Latin horror, from horrere ‘tremble, shudder’ (see horrid).
Middle English: from Old French hospitalier, from medieval Latin hospitalarius, from hospitale (see hospital).
From Romanian, from Ukrainian hospodar; related to Russian gospodarʹ, from gospodʹ ‘lord’.
Early 20th century: from French hôtelier, from Old French hostelier ‘innkeeper’ (see hostelry).
Late Middle English; earliest use found in The Prymer, or lay folks' prayer book. From house + -er.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Documents Senate State New York 1840.
Late 17th century: from Dutch houwitser, from German Haubitze, from Czech houfnice ‘catapult’.
Middle English (in the sense ‘retailer at a stall, hawker’): probably of Low German origin.
Early 20th century (originally US): of unknown origin.
Early 20th century: from humid, on the pattern of cuspidor.
Old English hungor (noun), hyngran (verb), of Germanic origin; related to Dutch honger and German Hunger.
Early 18th century: probably related to Dutch huiken and German hocken.
From Hungarian huszár, from Old Serbian husar, from Italian corsaro (see corsair).
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in William Carpenter (1813–1885), biologist and university administrator. From ideo- + motor.
Late Middle English: from Old French idolatre, based on Greek eidōlolatrēs, from eidōlon (see idol) + -latrēs ‘worshipper’.
Ottoman Turkish ifṭār, from Arabic ifṭar ‘break a fast’.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in John Metham (fl. 1448). From classical Latin imāgināt-, past participial stem of imāgināri imagine + -or. Compare post-classical Latin imaginator maker of images or statues, forger, contriver.
1940s: from imagine, on the pattern of engineer.
1970s; earliest use found in European Journal Cancer. From immuno- + modulator, after immunomodulation.

Late 16th century (in early use spelled imposture, and sometimes confused with imposture in meaning): from French imposteur, from late Latin impostor, contraction of impositor, from Latin imponere (see impose).
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in William Godwin (1756–1836), philosopher and novelist. From improvise + -or.
Late 17th century: from medieval Latin, literally ‘cutter’, from Latin incis- (see incise).
Mid 19th century: from Latin inclinare ‘to incline’ + -meter.
Early 17th century; earliest use found in John Guillim (1550–1621), herald. From include + -er.
Mid 17th century (in the sense ‘a person who inducts or initiates’): from late Latin, from Latin inducere (see induce), or from induct + -or. Current senses date from the early 20th century.
Late Middle English (in inferior (sense 2 of the adjective)): from Latin, comparative of inferus ‘low’.
Mid 19th century: from in, on the pattern of outlier.
Old English innerra, innra, comparative of in.
Late Middle English: from French inquisiteur, from Latin inquisitor, from the verb inquirere (see enquire).
Late 19th century: from Latin, literally ‘form, likeness’.

Early 16th century (as an adjective meaning ‘entire, whole’): from Latin, ‘intact, whole’, from in- (expressing negation) + the root of tangere ‘to touch’. Compare with entire, also with integral, integrate, and integrity.
Late 15th century: from Latin, ‘inner’, comparative adjective from inter ‘within’.
Early 16th century: modern Latin, from Latin interlocut- ‘interrupted (by speech)’, from the verb interloqui, from inter- ‘between’ + loqui ‘speak’.
Mid 16th century: from Anglo-Norman French enterpleder, from enter- ‘between’ + pleder ‘to plead’.
Early 17th century: from Scottish Gaelic inbhir.
Late Middle English. From iron + worker. Compare ironwork.
Late Middle English (in the sense ‘not conforming to rule (especially that of the Church’)): via Old French from medieval Latin irregularis, from in- ‘not’ + regularis (see regular).
Mid 19th century: from Greek isobaros ‘of equal weight’, from isos ‘equal’ + baros ‘weight’.
Mid 19th century: from Greek isomerēs ‘sharing equally’, from isos ‘equal’ + meros ‘a share’.
Named after B. K. S. Iyengar (1918–2014), the Indian yoga teacher who devised this method.
Mid 19th century (applied to any predatory seabird): from German Jäger ‘hunter’, from jagen ‘to hunt’.
Early 17th century: from Portuguese, from Tupi-Guarani yaguára.
Mid 16th century: from Latin, from janua ‘door’.
Late 16th century: from French jarre, from Arabic jarra.
Middle English (originally denoting any bright-coloured chalcedony other than carnelian): from Old French jasp(r)e, from Latin iaspis, from Greek, of oriental origin.
Mid 19th century: from jerk + water, from the need for early railway engines to be supplied with water in remote areas, by dipping a bucket into a stream and ‘jerking’ it out by rope.
Late 18th century (in an earlier sense). From jet + -er.
Mid 16th century (originally a slang word for a door): from the verb jig.
Late 17th century (in the sense ‘broker, middleman’, originally not derogatory): from job.
Early 19th century; earliest use found in The Sporting Magazine. From job + master.
Late Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French, from Old French joindre ‘to join’.
Late 19th century (in Australian sense ‘a clergyman’): from joss + -er.
Early 17th century. From post-classical Latin iudicator person who judges from classical Latin iūdicāt-, past participial stem of iūdicāre to judge + -or.
Late 16th century: from late Latin jugularis, from Latin jugulum ‘collarbone, throat’, diminutive of jugum ‘yoke’.

Mid 19th century (in jumper (sense 2 of the noun)): probably from dialect jump ‘short coat’, perhaps from Scots jupe ‘a man's (later also a woman's) loose jacket or tunic’, via Old French from Arabic jubba. Compare with jibba.
Middle English (as an adjective following a family name): from Latin, comparative of juvenis ‘young’.
Late Middle English: from Latin juniperus.
Late Middle English: from Old French jureor, from Latin jurator, from jurare ‘swear’, from jus, jur- ‘law’.
Late 15th century: from medieval Latin justitiarius (see justiciary).

Middle English cayser, from Old Norse keisari, based on Latin Caesar (see Caesar), and later reinforced by Middle Dutch keiser. The modern English form (early 19th century) derives from German Kaiser.
Mid 19th century: German, from Kapelle ‘court orchestra’ (from medieval Latin capella ‘chapel’) + Meister ‘master’.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Proceedings of the Royal Society of London. From the name of Karl Kellner, German optical instrument maker, who introduced the eyepiece in 1849.
Mid 19th century (originally a miners' term): German.
Mid 19th century: from Urdu and Persian ḵabar, from Arabic.
Late 19th century: representing a pronunciation of Arabic ḵawr ‘low land between two stretches of higher ground’.
Late 16th century: from Old Norse ker ‘container, tub’.
Used originally with reference to the Earl of Warwick (see Warwick, Richard Neville).
Old English cypera (in kipper (sense 2 of the noun)), of Germanic origin; related to Old Saxon kupiro, perhaps also to copper.
Late 18th century: from Afrikaans, from Dutch klip ‘rock’ + springer ‘jumper’.

Late 16th century (originally denoting a harness-maker, then a slaughterer of horses): possibly from obsolete knack ‘trinket’. The word also had the sense ‘old worn-out horse’ (late 18th century). knacker (sense 2 of the noun) may be from dialect knacker ‘castanet’, from obsolete knack ‘make a sharp abrupt noise’, of imitative origin. It is unclear whether the verb represents a figurative use of ‘slaughter’, from knacker (sense 1 of the noun), or of ‘castrate’, from knacker (sense 2 of the noun).

Mid 19th century (originally in knickerbocker (sense 2)): named after Diedrich Knickerbocker, pretended author of W. Irving's History of New York (1809). knickerbocker (sense 1) is said to have arisen from the resemblance of knickerbockers to the knee breeches worn by Dutch men in George Cruikshank's illustrations in Irving's book.
South African Dutch, from Dutch leger, lager ‘camp’. Compare with lager, lair, and leaguer.
Early 20th century: named after the Labrador Peninsula, where the breed was developed. The name Labrador dog had been applied in the 19th century to a much larger breed, similar to the Newfoundland.
Late 16th century (denoting lac): from obsolete French lacre ‘sealing wax’, from Portuguese laca (see lac).
Old English hlǣd(d)er, of West Germanic origin; related to Dutch leer and German Leiter.
Spanish, from Latin lacus, denoting a vat for freshly pressed wine.
Mid 19th century: from German Lagerbier ‘beer brewed for keeping’, from Lager ‘storehouse’. Compare with laager, lair, and leaguer.
Early 19th century: from German Lämmergeier, from Lämmer (plural of Lamm ‘lamb’) + Geier ‘vulture’.
Late 16th century: from French lancier, from lance ‘a lance’.

Middle English: via Old French from Latin, from languere (see languish). The original sense was ‘illness, distress’, later ‘faintness, lassitude’; current senses date from the 18th century, when such lassitude became associated with a romantic yearning.
Late Middle English: from Old French lanier, perhaps a noun use of lanier ‘cowardly’, from a derogatory use of lanier ‘wool merchant’, from Latin lanarius, from lana ‘wool’.
Early 19th century: from Latin, literally ‘household god’.
Middle English (denoting a store of meat): from Old French lardier, from medieval Latin lardarium, from laridum (see lard).
Early 17th century: from Portuguese lascari, from Urdu and Persian laškarī ‘soldier’, from laškar ‘army’.
1960s: acronym from light amplification by stimulated emission of radiation, on the pattern of maser.
Mid 16th century. From last + -er<br>mid 19th century. From last + -er.
Old English læthor (denoting washing soda or its froth), lēthran (verb), of Germanic origin; related to Old Norse lauthr (noun), from an Indo-European root shared by Greek loutron ‘bath’.
Old English lætra ‘slower’, comparative of læt (see late).
Old English hleahtor, of Germanic origin; related to German Gelächter, also to laugh.
Middle English (as a noun denoting a person who washes linen): contraction of lavender, from Old French lavandier, based on Latin lavanda ‘things to be washed’, from lavare ‘to wash’.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French lavendre, based on medieval Latin lavandula.
Late Old English (as the name of a water plant mentioned by Pliny), from Latin. The current sense dates from the early 17th century.
Middle English: from medieval Latin lazarus, with biblical allusion to Lazarus, the name of a beggar covered in sores (Luke 16:20).
Late 16th century: from Dutch leger ‘camp’. Compare with laager, lager, and lair.
Old English lether, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch leer and German Leder, from an Indo-European root shared by Irish leathar and Welsh lledr.
Middle English: from Old French lichiere, lecheor, from lechier ‘live in debauchery or gluttony’, ultimately of West Germanic origin and related to lick.
Late Middle English: from Latin, from lect- ‘read, chosen’, from the verb legere.

Late Middle English legger, ligger (denoting a large bible or breviary), probably from variants of lay and lie, influenced by Dutch legger and ligger. Current senses date from the 16th century, except the fishing senses, known from the 17th century.
Mid 16th century (in the general sense ‘look sideways or askance’): perhaps from obsolete leer ‘cheek’, from Old English hlēor, as though the sense were ‘to glance over one's cheek’.
Mid 17th century: from Latin, from legat- ‘deputed, delegated, bequeathed’, from the verb legare.
Mid 16th century: from Old Norse ljóstr, from ljósta ‘to strike’.
Late Middle English: probably from an attributive use of leper ‘leprosy’, from Old French lepre, via Latin from Greek lepra, feminine of lepros ‘scaly’, from lepos, lepis ‘scale’.
Early 17th century: from Latin, literally ‘a person who lifts’, from levare ‘raise, lift’.
Middle English: from Old French levier, leveor, from lever ‘to lift’.
Latin, perhaps related to ligare ‘to bind’.
1970s (in lifestyler (sense 1)): from lifestyle + -er; sense 2 dates from the 1980s and is derived from lifestyle block.
Mid 16th century (as an adjective): perhaps from limber in the dialect sense ‘cart shaft’, with allusion to the to-and-fro motion.
Early 20th century: from German, from Lippiza, site of the former Austrian Imperial stud near Trieste.
Late 16th century: modern Latin, apparently formed irregularly from Latin liquidus ‘liquid’ + medieval Latin ambar ‘amber’.
Middle English (denoting liquid or something to drink): from Old French lic(o)ur, from Latin liquor; related to liquare ‘liquefy’, liquere ‘be fluid’.
Middle English (in litter (sense 5 of the noun)): from Old French litiere, from medieval Latin lectaria, from Latin lectus ‘bed’. Sense 1 dates from the mid 18th century.
Old English lopustre, alteration of Latin locusta ‘crustacean, locust’.
Middle English: from lode in the obsolete sense ‘way, course’ + star.
Late Middle English: perhaps from Middle Dutch loteren ‘wag about’.
Early 19th century; earliest use found in Cobbett's Weekly Political Register. From lower + -er.
Late Middle English: perhaps via Old French lobeor ‘swindler, parasite’ from lober ‘deceive’.

Old English, from Latin, ‘light-bringing, morning star’, from lux, luc- ‘light’ + -fer ‘bearing’. Lucifer (sense 1) is by association with the ‘son of the morning’ (Isa. 14:12), believed by Christian interpreters to be a reference to Satan.
Early 20th century: named after Georg Luger (1849–1923), Austrian firearms expert.
Mid 17th century: from medieval Latin lumbaris, from Latin lumbus ‘loin’.
Late Middle English lomere, perhaps symbolic of clumsy movement.
Early 16th century (in lurcher (sense 2)): from obsolete lurch ‘remain in a place furtively’, variant of lurk.
Late 19th century: from French, from luth ‘lute’.
Early 19th century: from German dialect, originally denoting a kind of crater lake in the Eifel district of Germany.
Mid 17th century: earlier form of Makassar. The oil was originally represented as consisting of ingredients from Makassar.
Middle English: from Old French massier, from masse (see mace).
Old English mædere, of Germanic origin; obscurely related to Dutch mede, in the same sense.
Mid 19th century. From Welsh maenor, maenol administrative district, manor, perhaps from maen stone + adjectival ending -awr.
Early 19th century; earliest use found in William Kirkpatrick (1754–1812), army officer in the East India Company and diplomatist. From Magar Magar, self-designation.
Late 17th century (in an earlier sense). From magazine + -er.
1970s; earliest use found in Business Week. From mainframe + -er.
1960s; earliest use found in The New Left Review. From mainstream + -er.
Middle English: from Latin, comparative of magnus ‘great’; perhaps influenced by French majeur.
Late Middle English: (in the spelling maker, a sense of maker); the Scottish spelling dates from the late 15th century, while the modern use originated in the 21st century.
Late Middle English: from Latin, from malefact- ‘done wrong’, from the verb malefacere, from male ‘ill’ + facere ‘do’.
Early 19th century: back-formation from malingerer, apparently from French malingre, perhaps formed as mal- ‘wrongly’ + haingre ‘weak’, probably of Germanic origin.
Middle English: from Old French mangeure, based on Latin manducat- ‘chewed’ (see manducate).
Middle English: from Old French maniere, based on Latin manuarius ‘of the hand’, from manus ‘hand’.
Late 19th century. From the name of Ferdinand Ritter von Mannlicher, Austrian engineer and firearms designer.
Mid 18th century: from French manomètre, from Greek manos ‘thin’ + -mètre ‘(instrument) measuring’.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French maner ‘dwelling’, from Latin manere ‘remain’.
Middle English: from Old French marinier, from medieval Latin marinarius, from Latin marinus (see marine).
1950s: acronym from microwave amplification by the stimulated emission of radiation.
Old English mæg(i)ster (later reinforced by Old French maistre), from Latin magister; probably related to magis ‘more’.
Spanish, literally ‘killer’, from matar ‘to kill’, from Persian māt ‘dead’; senses relating to games are extended uses, expressing a notion of ‘dominance’.
Middle English: via Old French from Latin materia ‘timber, substance’, also ‘subject of discourse’, from mater ‘mother’.
Mid 18th century. Perhaps from Dutch mager meagre, lean; probably showing independent borrowings in Jamaican and U.S. regional English.
Late 19th century: named after Paul von Mauser (1838–1914), German inventor.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in Promptorium Parvulorum. Origin uncertain; perhaps originally a variant of mother, with early shortening of Old English and Middle English long close ō (attested by spellings with modd-) and subsequent relengthening. A contracted form is common, chiefly in vocative use, in East Anglia.
Middle English: from Old French maire, from the Latin adjective major ‘greater’, used as a noun in late Latin.
Late 16th century (as a noun): from Latin maeander, from Greek Maiandros, the name of a river (see Menderes).
Mid 19th century (in an earlier sense). From medicate + -or.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in Guy de Chauliac's Grande Chirurgie. From medicine + -er. Compare Anglo-Norman medicinour, Middle French medecineur, medicineur, Middle High German mediziner.
Late Middle English: from Old French medler, from medle ‘medlar fruit’, from Latin mespila, from Greek mespilē, mespilon.
1980s; earliest use found in The New York Times.
1980s; earliest use found in Newsweek. From mega- + seller, after bestseller.
Early 20th century; earliest use found in The Los Angeles Times. Shortened from mellerdrammer<br>mid 19th century; earliest use found in The Atlantic Monthly. Probably from mell + -er.
Middle English: via Old French from Latin membrum ‘limb’.
