Mid 18th century: via French and Latin from Greek Mentōr, the name of the adviser of the young Telemachus in Homer's Odyssey.
Middle English: from Old French mercier, based on Latin merx, merc- ‘goods’.
Mid 17th century: modern Latin, from Latin mergus ‘diver’ (from mergere ‘to dive’) + anser ‘goose’.
1940s; earliest use found in Bombers over Merseyside. From the name of Merseyside + -er.
1970s; earliest use found in All England Law Reports. From the name of the litigants in the 1973 Court of Appeal case of Mesher v. Mesher.
Early 20th century (as an adjective): variant of meshuga.
1990s; earliest use found in International Management. From message + -er.
Middle English: from Old Northern French messanger, variant of Old French messager, from Latin missus (see message).

Mid 16th century; earliest use found in William Painter (?1540–1594), translator and administrator. From Italian messere, (before a title) messer, title of respect given to persons of importance, especially jurors, notaries, etc. from French mes sire.
Mid 17th century (in an earlier sense). From classical Latin messor a reaper, harvester from mess-, past participial stem of metere to reap, cognate with mow + -or.
1960s; earliest use found in Mind. From meta- + character.
Late 15th century: from French métaphore, via Latin from Greek metaphora, from metapherein ‘to transfer’.
Mid 16th century (denoting any atmospheric phenomenon): from modern Latin meteorum, from Greek meteōron, neuter (used as a noun) of meteōros ‘lofty’.
Middle English (in the sense ‘person who measures’): from mete + -er. The current sense dates from the 19th century.
Late 18th century: French, based on Latin ministerium ‘service’.
Early 20th century; earliest use found in Journal of Infectious Diseases.
1980s; earliest use found in The Economist. From microlight + -er.
1920s; earliest use found in Science. From micro- + manipulator, after micromanipulation.
1960s; earliest use found in Current Anthropology. From micro- + wear.
Late Middle English (originally in the sense ‘native of Milan’, later ‘a vendor of fancy goods from Milan’): from Milan + -er.

Mid 17th century; earliest use found in Thomas Herbert. From Urdu and Persian mīnār tower, minaret from Arabic manār (masculine) lighthouse and manāra (feminine) lighthouse, tower, minaret, nouns of place from nāra.
Early 20th century; earliest use found in The Times. From German Minenwerfer from Minen-, combining form of Mine + Werfer thrower, mortar.
1940s; earliest use found in Railway Gazette. From mini- + printer.

Middle English (in minister (sense 2 of the noun)); also in the sense ‘a person acting under the authority of another’): from Old French ministre (noun), ministrer (verb), from Latin minister ‘servant’, from minus ‘less’.
1980s; earliest use found in Forbes. Shortened from minisupercomputer.
1980s; earliest use found in Forbes. From mini- + supercomputer.
Middle English: from Old French menu vair ‘little vair’, from menu ‘little’ + vair ‘squirrel fur’ (see vair).

Middle English: from Latin, ‘smaller, less’; related to minuere ‘lessen’. The term originally denoted a Franciscan friar, suggested by the Latin name Fratres Minores ( ‘Lesser Brethren’), chosen by St Francis for the order.
Old English mynster, via ecclesiastical Latin from Greek monastērion (see monastery).
Late 17th century: from Spanish, from mirar ‘to look’.
Middle English: from Old French mirour, based on Latin mirare ‘look at’. Early senses also included ‘a crystal used in magic’ and ‘a person deserving imitation’.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in The Southern Quarterly Review. From mis- + calculator, after miscalculate.
Late 15th century (as an adjective in the sense ‘miserly’): from Latin, literally ‘wretched’.
Late 17th century. From mis- + manager, perhaps after mismanaging, mismanagement.
Late Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French, from the Old French verb mesnommer, from mes- ‘wrongly’ + nommer ‘to name’ (based on Latin nomen ‘name’).
Mid 16th century: weakened form of master in unstressed use before a name.
Late 17th century: of unknown origin; compare with Welsh moedrodd ‘to worry, bother’.
Mid 17th century. From Manx maor, cognate with Scottish Gaelic and Irish maor; compare mormaor.
1940s. From French Modulor from module + or, hence ‘module of the golden section’.
Early 16th century (in monitor (sense 3 of the noun)): from Latin, from monit- ‘warned’, from the verb monere. monitor (sense 1 of the noun) dates from the 1930s.
Italian, on the pattern of French Monseigneur.
Late Middle English: from Old French monstre, from Latin monstrum ‘portent or monster’, from monere ‘warn’.
Early 20th century. From Montélimar, the name of a town in the department of Drôme in southern France.
Old English mōr, of Germanic origin.

Early 19th century; earliest use found in George Chalmers (d. 1825), antiquary and political writer. From Scottish Gaelic mórmhaor (also maor mór), altered form of mormhar, through analysis of its first element as mór great.
Late Old English (in mortar (sense 2 of the noun)), from Old French mortier, from Latin mortarium (to which the English spelling was later assimilated).
Early 18th century; earliest use found in Ephraim Chambers (?1680–1740), encyclopaedist. From French mortier.
Old English mōdor, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch moeder and German Mutter, from an Indo-European root shared by Latin mater and Greek mētēr.
Late 19th century (in an earlier sense). From mother + -er.
Late Middle English (denoting a person who imparts motion): from Latin, literally ‘mover’, based on movere ‘to move’. The current sense of the noun dates from the mid 19th century.
Mid 16th century: perhaps from mould, but compare with Norwegian dialect muldra ‘crumble’.
Middle English: from muck + -er; mucker (sense 2) probably from the phrase muck in. mucker (sense 3) is probably from German Mucker ‘sulky person’.
Mid 17th century; earliest use found in John Davies (1625–1693), translator. From Tamil mutaliyār, plural of mutali a chief from mutal best.
Via Spanish from Arabic mudajjan ‘allowed to stay’.
From Arabic muḵtār, passive participle of iḵtāra ‘choose’.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Arthur Cayley (1821–1895), mathematician. From multi- + planar.
1950s; earliest use found in Journal of the Royal Statistical Society. From multi- + server.
Late Middle English: from Old French momeur, from momer ‘act in a mime’; perhaps of Germanic origin.

Old English morthor, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch moord and German Mord, from an Indo-European root shared by Sanskrit mará ‘death’ and Latin mors; reinforced in Middle English by Old French murdre.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in New York Weekly Herald. From mustang + -er.
Late Middle English: from Old French moustrer (verb), moustre (noun), from Latin monstrare ‘to show’.
Late Middle English: imitative; compare with German dialect muttern.
Late 19th century; earliest use found in Harper's Magazine. Representing a regional (especially cockney) or colloquial pronunciation of mother.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in William Hodge Mill (1792–1853), orientalist. From mythicize + -er.
Early 20th century. From Afrikaans naar from Dutch naar dismal, unpleasant.
Late 18th century: from thieves' slang, of unknown origin.

Old English; earliest use found in Orosius' History. Comparative of nigh. In later use (in Middle English) partly also from early Scandinavian; see further note below<br>Middle English; earliest use found in The Chronicle of Robert of Gloucester. From early Scandinavian (compare Old Icelandic naer, adverb, ‘nearer, near’, Old Icelandic naerr, adverb, ‘nearer’, representing a double comparative formation from the Scandinavian base of Old Icelandic naer + the Scandinavian base of Old Icelandic -r, and Old Icelandic naerri, adverb, ‘nearer, near’, probably originally an adjectival formation). Old Icelandic naer, naerri were used in both comparative and positive sense; in modern Icelandic naer (the reflex of both naer and naerr) is used only in comparative sense (except in compounds), and naerri only in positive sense.
Early 19th century (in the dialect sense ‘grumble, fret’): imitative.
1940s. Either from the initial letters of navigation and ranging, or from nav- + -ar.

Mid 18th century. From Urdu naẕr gift from Persian naẕr undertaking, offering promised or made in consequence of a vow from Arabic naḏr vow, votive offering from naḏara to vow, dedicate, consecrate.
Early 20th century. From German Neanderthaler, Neandertaler from Neanderthal, Neandertal + -er.
1940s; earliest use found in Hutchinson's Pictorial History of the War. From German Nebelwerfer from Nebel mist, fog, haze + Werfer thrower, mortar.
Early 20th century: from Nebuchadnezzar (see Nebuchadnezzar II).
1980s; earliest use found in The British Medical Journal. From nebu- + -haler.
Mid 16th century (in nectar (sense 2)): via Latin from Greek nektar.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in Guy de Chauliac's Grande Chirurgie. From post-classical Latin nenufar water lily from Arabic naynūfar (also as nīnūfar), probably transmission error for nīlūfar from Persian nīlūfar, nīlūpar, also nīlūfal, nīlūpal from Sanskrit nīlotpala blue lotus from nīla dark blue + utpala lotus, water-lily. Compare French nénufar, Spanish nenúfar, Italian nenufaro.
1960s; earliest use found in Science. From neuro- + modulator.
Late Middle English: via Old French from Latin neuter ‘neither’, from ne- ‘not’ + uter ‘either’.
Old English nǣfre, from ne ‘not’ + ǣfre ‘ever’.
Late 16th century: from earlier neger, after Latin niger ‘black’ (see Negro).
Late 19th century; earliest use found in ‘Price Warung’ (1855–1911) (real name William Astley). From nine + -er.
Early 20th century. From scientific Latin Nitrobacter, genus name from nitro- + bacter- (in bacterium).
Early 20th century: from Latin nocere ‘to harm’ + receptor.
1940s; earliest use found in Journal of the American Chemical Society. From nona- + -mer.
1940s; earliest use found in Evening News. From Norland + -er.
Mid 18th century (in an earlier sense). From nose + -er.
Old English, from Latin, from novem ‘nine’ (being originally the ninth month of the Roman year).
Early 20th century; earliest use found in Nature: a weekly journal of science. From nucleate + -or.
Middle English: from Old French nombre (noun), nombrer (verb), from Latin numerus.

Early 19th century; earliest use found in John Loudon (1783–1843), landscape gardener and horticultural writer. From scientific Latin Nuphar, shortened form of Arabic nīnūfar. Compare also Middle French neufard, French regional (Haute-Marne) nufa.
Old English ār, of Germanic origin; related to Danish and Norwegian åre.
1950s: from oat, with allusion to horse feed; compare with the synonym horse opera.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in The Southern Literary Messenger. From obfuscate + -or.
Latin, originally as the phrase ob itur ‘by the way’.

Early 16th century (in an earlier sense). From Middle French, French observateur a person who observes a law, a person who makes (scientific) observations and its etymon classical Latin observātor a person who watches over something, in post-classical Latin also a person who observes a law or practice (early 3rd cent. in Tertullian) from observāt-, past participial stem of observāre + -or.
1920s; earliest use found in Proceedings of the Royal Society of London. From occlude + -er.
1970s: alteration of Oscar, popularized by the name of a character in an Australian television series (1965–8).
1920s; earliest use found in Chemical Abstracts. From octa- + -mer.
Late Old English, from Latin, from octo ‘eight’ (being originally the eighth month of the Roman year).
Late 16th century: from late Latin ocularis, from Latin oculus ‘eye’.
Late 18th century: from French odomètre, from Greek hodos ‘way’ + -meter.

Old English offrian ‘sacrifice something to a deity’, of Germanic origin, from Latin offerre ‘bestow, present’ (in ecclesiastical Latin ‘offer to God’), reinforced by French offrir (which continued to express the primary sense). The noun ( late Middle English) is from French offre.
Middle English: via Anglo-Norman French from medieval Latin officiarius, from Latin officium (see office).
Early 19th century: from old, on the pattern of youngster.
Early 16th century: from medieval Latin, of unknown ultimate origin.
Mid 16th century (in an earlier sense). From on- + setter, after to set on ——, to set on, or onset.
1920s; earliest use found in Brain: a journal of neurology. From opto- + motor.
Middle English: from Old French ordre, from Latin ordo, ordin- ‘row, series, rank’.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in Regiam Majestatem. From classical Latin ōrdinātor a person who regulates or controls, a person who institutes, in post-classical Latin also a person who ordains to the Christian ministry, God as governor or ordainer from ōrdināt-, past participial stem of ōrdināre + -or.
Mid 17th century: Channel Islands French, from French ormier, from Latin auris maris ‘ear of the sea’ (because the ormer resembles an ear in shape).
Early 19th century; earliest use found in The Saturday Evening Post. From ornament + -er.
Early 20th century: coined in French as ornithoptère.
One of the several speculative stories of its origin claims that the statuette reminded Margaret Herrick, an executive director of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, of her uncle Oscar.
Late Middle English: from Old French; compare with medieval Latin auseria ‘osier bed’.
Late Middle English: from Old French hostelier ‘innkeeper’, from hostel (see hostel).
Old English ōther, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch and German ander, from an Indo-European root meaning ‘different’.
Old English otr, ot(t)or, of Germanic origin; related to Greek hudros ‘water snake’.
Late Middle English: from out + -er, replacing earlier utter.
Late Middle English; earliest use found in The Wycliffite Bible (early version). From out- + goer, after go or outgo.
Mid 18th century: perhaps influenced by the obsolete nautical term outligger, in the same sense.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Peter Hawker (1786–1853), army officer and writer. From outskirt + -er. Compare later outskirt.

Mid 19th century; earliest use found in United States Magazine and Democratic Review. From French ouvrier worker from classical Latin operārius labourer, use as noun of masculine singular of operārius used in work or labouring.

Old English ofer, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch over and German über, from an Indo-European word (originally a comparative of the element represented by -ove in above) which is also the base of Latin super and Greek huper.

Old English (in an earlier sense). Cognate with or formed similarly to Middle Dutch overdore, Old Saxon oberdure, Old High German ubarturi (Middle High German übertüre, early modern German überthüre) from the Germanic base of over- + the Germanic base of door.
Early 20th century; earliest use found in William De Morgan (1839–1917), potter and novelist. From overdraw + -er.
Late 16th century; earliest use found in Barnaby Rich (1542–1617), soldier and author. From overhear + -er.
Late 19th century; earliest use found in The Pall Mall Gazette. From over- + matter.
1980s; earliest use found in The Chicago Tribune. From overpronate + -or.
Late 16th century; earliest use found in Philip Sidney (1554–1586), author and courtier. From overrule + -er, probably partly after ruler.
1990s; earliest use found in Runner's World.
Late Middle English (in an earlier sense). From owe + -er.
Middle English: from Old French oistre, via Latin from Greek ostreon; related to osteon ‘bone’ and ostrakon ‘shell or tile’.
Early 19th century; earliest use found in Edward Bulwer-Lytton (1803–1873), writer and politician. From pad + -er<br>1920s; earliest use found in The Times. Probably from pad- + -er.
Late 16th century; earliest use found in Anthony Copley (b. 1567), writer and conspirator. From the plural of pain + taker, after painstaking.
Mid 18th century (in the sense ‘a talk between tribespeople and traders’): from Portuguese palavra ‘word’, from Latin parabola ‘comparison’ (see parable).
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French, from medieval Latin palmarius ‘pilgrim’, from Latin palma ‘palm’.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Edward Newman (1801–1876), naturalist. From either palp or palpus + -ifer.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Edward Newman (1801–1876), naturalist. From post-classical Latin palpus palp + -ger carrying, carrier.
Late Middle English (as a noun): from Pandare, the name of a character in Chaucer's Troilus and Criseyde (see Pandarus). The verb dates from the early 17th century.
Middle English: from Old French panier, from Latin panarium ‘bread basket’, from panis ‘bread’.

Middle English; earliest use found in The Chronicle of Robert of Gloucester. From Anglo-Norman paneter, panetier, pannetier, paintier pantry-man, panter, baker and Old French, Middle French, French panetier, pannetier panter, baker from pain bread + -etier, extended form of -ier (compare Middle French, French † paneter to knead bread, to supply with bread). Compare Old Occitan panatier, panetier, Catalan paneter, Spanish panadero, Italian panettiere, post-classical Latin panaterius, panetarius, paneterius, panitarius baker, officer in charge of the pantry<br>late 17th century (in an earlier sense). From pant + -er.

Middle English: from Old French pantere, from Latin panthera, from Greek panthēr. In Latin, pardus ‘leopard’ also existed; the two terms led to confusion: until the mid 19th century many taxonomists regarded the panther and the leopard as separate species.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in Robert Mannyng (d. c1338), poet and historian. Probably variant of panter, perhaps after butler. There is no equivalent form attested in French or in post-classical Latin, although compare post-classical Latin pantleria pantry.
Late 19th century: via Latin from Greek, ‘ruler over all’.
From German Panzer, literally ‘coat of mail’.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French papir, from Latin papyrus ‘paper-reed’ (see papyrus). The verb dates from the late 16th century.
1960s; earliest use found in The Times.
Late 16th century (in the sense ‘equality of value or standing’): from Latin, ‘equal’, also ‘equality’. The golf term dates from the late 19th century.
1920s. From para- + ancient Greek χορός dance, but taken by S. Sugden as if having the sense ‘space’, by mistake for χώρα.
Mid 17th century: modern Latin, from Greek para- ‘beside’ + metron ‘measure’.
Mid 16th century; earliest use found in Thomas Elyot (c1490–1546), humanist and diplomat. Partly from parget + -er, and partly from Middle French (Liège) porgeteur plasterer.
From the name of Antoine A. Parmentier (1737–1813), the French agriculturalist who popularized the potato in France.
Late Middle English: from Old French particuler, from Latin particularis ‘concerning a small part’, from particula ‘small part’.

Middle English: alteration of parcener ‘partner, joint heir’, from Anglo-Norman French parcener, based on Latin partitio(n-) ‘partition’. The change in the first syllable was due to association with part.
Middle English: from the Old French adjective passager ‘passing, transitory’, used as a noun, from passage (see passage).
From pass over ‘pass without touching’, with reference to the exemption of the Israelites from the death of their firstborn (Exod. 12).
Late Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French pastour, from Latin pastor ‘shepherd’, from past- ‘fed, grazed’, from the verb pascere.
Old English, from Latin pater noster ‘our father’, the first words of the Lord's Prayer.
1920s; earliest use found in Journal of Philosophy. From patho- + -grapher, after pathography.
Early 16th century (in an earlier sense). From patter + -er.

Late 15th century: from Latin, literally ‘poor’. The word's use in English originated in the Latin legal phrase in forma pauperis, literally ‘in the form of a poor person’ (allowing non-payment of costs).
Old English pere, peru, of West Germanic origin; related to Dutch peer, from Latin pirum.

Late Middle English (in the sense ‘particular’): from Latin peculiaris ‘of private property’, from peculium ‘property’, from pecu ‘cattle’ (cattle being private property). The sense ‘strange’ dates from the early 17th century.
Middle English: perhaps an alteration of synonymous dialect pedder, apparently from dialect ped ‘pannier’.
Early 18th century: from French pédomètre, from Latin pes, ped- ‘foot’.
Late 16th century: perhaps a variant of dialect pire or perhaps partly from a shortening of appear.
Early 17th century; earliest use found in Randle Cotgrave (fl. 1587–?1630), lexicographer. From peg + -er.
1940s. From pellet + -izer. Compare slightly later pelletize, pelletized, pelletization, pelletizing, and also pelleter.
Early 19th century; earliest use found in Duke of Wellington (1769–1852), army officer and prime minister. From pen + holder.
Early 16th century: via Latin from Greek pentametros (see penta-, -meter).
Mid 16th century; earliest use found in William Painter (?1540–1594), translator and administrator. From people + -er.
Old English piper, pipor, of West Germanic origin; related to Dutch peper and German Pfeffer; via Latin from Greek peperi, from Sanskrit pippalī ‘berry, peppercorn’.
Middle English; earliest use found in Hustings Rolls. From pepper + -er, probably after Anglo-Norman peverer.
Latin, ‘through, by means of’; partly via Old French.

Late 16th century; earliest use found in John Banister (1532/3–?1610), surgeon. From classical Latin perfector person who brings to completion or perfection from perfect-, past participial stem of perficere to accomplish + -or.
1920s; earliest use found in The Chronicle-Telegram. Apparently from perfume + -ier. Compare Middle French, French † parfumier, Italian profumiere.
Late Middle English: via Latin from Greek perimetros, based on peri- ‘around’ + metron ‘measure’.
Mid 16th century. From perjure + -or. Compare Anglo-Norman parjurour and Old French or Middle French perjureor.
Late Middle English (as an adverb meaning ‘at right angles’): via Old French from Latin perpendicularis, from perpendiculum ‘plumb line’, from per- ‘through’ + pendere ‘to hang’.
From the name of a spring at Vergèze, France, from which this water comes.
Middle English: from Old French peutre, of unknown origin.

Mid 19th century; earliest use found in William Thackeray (1811–1863), novelist. From German Pfarrer parish priest, pastor (Middle High German pharraere, late Old High German pharrāri) from Old High German pfarra, farra parish + -āri.
Late 19th century; earliest use found in Robert Muir (1864–1959), pathologist. From the name of Richard Pfeiffer, German bacteriologist.
Late 18th century: from French, from Greek phalangion ‘spider's web’ (because of the webbed toes of their hind feet).
1940s: from phase, on the pattern of vector.
Mid 18th century: from the earlier noun philander ‘man, husband’, often used in literature as the given name of a lover, from Greek philandros ‘fond of men’, from philein ‘to love’ + anēr ‘man’.
Mid 19th century. From phono- + -grapher, after phonography.
Early 17th century: from Latin phosphorus (see phosphorus).
Early 20th century; earliest use found in Science. From photo- + sensitizer.
1950s; earliest use found in American Midland Naturalist.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in Domesday Ipswich. From Anglo-Norman pepoudrous, pié poudrous (adjective) dusty-footed, (noun) wayfarer (1214; compare Middle French (Poitou) pyé pouldreux travelling merchant, French † pied poudreux person unable to pay, also Middle French, French † avoir les pieds poudreux to leave without paying) from pié foot + poudrus dusty (from poudre + -ous, -eux). Compare post-classical Latin pede-pulverosus wayfarer, itinerant merchant, lit. dusty of foot, dusty-footed (from classical Latin pede, ablative of pēs foot + post-classical Latin pulverosus).
Middle English: from medieval Latin pera, of unknown origin.
Late 16th century: from French pilastre, from Italian pilastro or medieval Latin pilastrum, from Latin pila ‘pillar’.

Late 16th century (in an earlier sense). Extended form of pilch, with apparently arbitrary ending<br>1920s; earliest use found in World's Paper Trade Review. Origin uncertain; probably related to pilch; compare pilcher.
Late Middle English (as a noun in the sense ‘action of pilfering, something pilfered’): from Old French pelfrer ‘to pillage’, of unknown origin. Compare with pelf.

Early 19th century; earliest use found in Robert Forby (1759–1825), philologist. Apparently from pile + gare, and hence representing a formation much earlier than the date of the earliest attestations below<br>early 20th century. From German Pilger, lit ‘pilgrim’, after Pilgerschrittwalzwerk, lit ‘pilgrim's steps rolling mill’, so called in allusion to the alternate feeding in and partial withdrawal of the billet during the operation of the mill, which is said to resemble the steps of pilgrims approaching a shrine<br>1940s; earliest use found in Metallurgia. From pilger.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French piler, based on Latin pila ‘pillar’.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French, from Old French pincier ‘to pinch’.
Middle English. From pind + -er. Compare earlier pounder and later poinder.
Early 20th century. From German Pinscher, of uncertain origin.
Early 16th century (as a military term denoting a member of the infantry): from French pionnier ‘foot soldier, pioneer’, Old French paonier, from paon, from Latin pedo, pedon- (see pawn).
Early 19th century; earliest use found in The Times. From pipe + layer.
1940s; earliest use found in Science. Partly from pipette + -or, and partly from pipette + -or.
1950s; earliest use found in Statesville (North Carolina) Record & Landmark. Probably from pip + -er.
Mid 16th century. From Middle French, French pistolier, from pistole + -ier.
From French Pithiviers, the name of a small town in the department of the Loiret.

Late 19th century; earliest use found in Defiance (Ohio) Democrat. From pit + -er. In later use also partly from pit + -er<br>early 19th century; earliest use found in The Edinburgh Review. Either shortened from pitter-patter, or variant of patter.
Early 19th century: from Latin American Spanish, literally ‘deposit, shoal’; related to placel ‘sandbank’, from plaza ‘a place’.
Mid 19th century: from French planimètre, from Latin planus ‘level’ + -mètre ‘(instrument) measuring’.
Early 18th century: from Latin plantaris, from planta ‘sole’.

Old English, denoting a bandage spread with a curative substance, from medieval Latin plastrum (shortening of Latin emplastrum, from Greek emplastron ‘daub, salve’), later reinforced by the Old French noun plastre. Sense 1 dates from late Middle English.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French plater, from plat ‘large dish’ (see plate).
1970s; earliest use found in The Times. From play + worker.
Late 17th century (in an earlier sense). From pleach + -er.
Mid 19th century (as a dialect word meaning ‘something large of its kind’): from the verb plonk + -er.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French, based on Latin pluvia ‘rain’.
Late Middle English (originally denoting a person dealing in and working with lead): from Old French plommier, from Latin plumbarius, from plumbum ‘lead’.
Middle English (in an earlier sense). In sense 1 apparently from plume + -er; compare later plumier.

Mid 17th century: from German plündern, literally ‘rob of household goods’, from Middle High German plunder ‘household effects’. Early use of the verb was with reference to the Thirty Years War (reflecting German usage); on the outbreak of the Civil War in 1642, the word and activity were associated with the forces under Prince Rupert.
Late 16th century: modern Latin, from Latin poeta ‘poet’ + -aster.
1950s: the name of a character in the animated television series Felix the Cat, noted for his intelligence and his use of scientific jargon.
Mid 19th century: from medieval Latin polaris ‘polar’ + -meter.
Early 17th century: from Dutch, from Middle Dutch polre.
Mid 19th century: short for pole bullock.
Mid 19th century: from German, from Greek polumeros ‘having many parts’, from polu- ‘many’ + meros ‘a share’.
Late 15th century: from Old French pome d'embre, from medieval Latin pomum de ambra ‘apple of ambergris’.
Early 20th century. From German Ponor and its etymon Serbian and Croatian ponor chasm, abyss.
Middle English: from Old French poure, from Latin pauper.
1930s: said to be from the name of William Poos (1891–1987), American entomologist.
Middle English: from Old French poplier, from Latin populus ‘poplar’.
Late Middle English (in the sense ‘prevalent among the general public’): from Latin popularis, from populus ‘people’. Sense 1 dates from the early 17th century.
Late Middle English (earlier as potager and pottinger): from Old French potager, from potage ‘contents of a pot’.
Late Middle English (in an earlier sense). Either from Anglo-Norman possessioner possessor, owner, or directly from possession + -er.
Early 16th century (as a plural noun denoting descendants): from Latin, comparative of posterus ‘following’, from post ‘after’.
Early 19th century; earliest use found in Anne Plumptre (1760–1818), writer and translator. From post + holder, ultimately after Dutch posthouder<br>1960s. From post + holder.
Mid 17th century: from French jardin potager ‘garden providing vegetables for the pot’.
Mid 17th century (in the sense ‘poke repeatedly’): frequentative of dialect pote ‘to push, kick, or poke’ of unknown origin.

Late Middle English. From Anglo-Norman poleter, poletier, pulter, pultere, pulleter, pulletere, pulletier and Old French, Middle French pouletier, Middle French poletier, poulletier from polet, poulet, poullet, pulet, pullet + -er, -ier. Compare post-classical Latin pulletarius poulterer (frequently 1241–1419 in British sources), poletarius, pultarius, pulterius.
Late 16th century: from archaic poulter, in the same sense, from Old French pouletier.
Early 18th century. From French pourparler negotiation, use as noun of the infinitive of pourparler.
Middle English: from Old French poudre, from Latin pulvis, pulver- ‘dust’.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French poeir, from an alteration of Latin posse ‘be able’.
Early 20th century; earliest use found in The Daily Northwestern. From powerboat + -er.
Mid 17th century; earliest use found in Richard Whitlock (b. ?1616).
Mid 16th century: extension of obsolete practitian, variant of practician.

Late 16th century; earliest use found in John Ferne (c1560–1609), administrator and writer on heraldry. From classical Latin praelector person who reads an author to others and adds explanations, in post-classical Latin also lecturer at a university from praelect-, past participial stem of praelegere + -or.
Mid 18th century: from praepositor, alteration of Latin praepositus ‘head, chief’, past participle of praeponere ‘set over’, from prae ‘ahead’ + ponere ‘to place’.
Latin, perhaps from prae ‘before’ + it- ‘gone’ (from the verb ire).
Early 17th century: from French précenteur or Latin praecentor, from praecent- ‘sung before’, from the verb praecinere, from prae ‘before’ + canere ‘sing’.
Late Middle English: from Latin praeceptor, from praecept- ‘warned, instructed’, from the verb praecipere (see precept).
Late Middle English: from Latin praecursor, from praecurs- ‘preceded’, from praecurrere, from prae ‘beforehand’ + currere ‘to run’.
1920s: from Latin praedator ‘plunderer’, from praedat- ‘seized as plunder’, from the verb praedari (see predation).
Late 19th century. From pre- + factor. Compare postfactor.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Scientific American. From preheat + -er.
Late 15th century: from Old French, ‘first’, from Latin primarius ‘principal’.

Late 15th century; earliest use found in Gilbert Hay (c1397–c1465), soldier and poet. From post-classical Latin praeparator person who prepares (early 3rd cent. in Tertullian, of John the Baptist) from classical Latin praeparāt-, past participial stem of praeparāre + -or.
Late 16th century: via ecclesiastical Latin from Greek presbuteros ‘elder’ (used in the New Testament to denote an elder of the early church), comparative of presbus ‘old (man)’.
Early 17th century; earliest use found in Joseph Swetnam (d. 1621), pamphleteer. From press + master.
Early 18th century: from Latin, literally ‘former, elder’, related to prae ‘before’.
Late Middle English: from Old French prisonier, from prison (see prison).
Mid 17th century: from private, on the pattern of volunteer.
Late Middle English (in an earlier sense). From prize + -er<br>mid 19th century. From prize + -er. Compare earlier prizeman and also prize winner.
Late 19th century; earliest use found in Overland Monthly. From either process or process + -er.
Late Middle English: contraction of procurator.
Middle English (denoting a steward): from Old French procuratour or Latin procurator ‘administrator, finance agent’, from procurat- ‘taken care of’, from the verb procurare (see procure).
Late Middle English: from Latin professor, from profess- ‘declared publicly’, from the verb profiteri (see profess).
Late 19th century (in an earlier sense). From profile + -ometer.
Late Middle English: from Old French progeniteur, from Latin progenitor, from progenit- ‘begotten’, from the verb progignere, from pro- ‘forward’ + gignere ‘beget’.
Late 16th century (in an earlier sense). From proportion + -er.
Early 20th century: from Latin proprius ‘own’ + receptor.
Mid 19th century: from late Latin, literally ‘anatomist’, based on Latin secare ‘to cut’, perhaps via French prosecteur.
1950s; earliest use found in Scientific Monthly.
1920s; earliest use found in Thomas Lowry (1874–1936), physical chemist. From proto- + -mer<br>1960s. From prot- + -o- + -mer.
Middle English: from Old French provendre, based on an alteration of Latin praebenda ‘things to be supplied’ (see prebend).
Late Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French provisour, from Latin provisor, from provis- ‘provided’ (see provision).
Mid 16th century; earliest use found in Richard Huloet (fl. 1552), lexicographer. From pry + -er.
Old English (p)saltere, via Latin psalterium from Greek psaltērion ‘stringed instrument’.
1930s; earliest use found in Science. From psycho- + biographer, after psychobiography.
Mid 19th century. From ancient Greek ψυκτήρ wine-cooler from ψύχειν to cool, of unknown origin, but distinct from ψύχειν to breathe, blow + -τήρ, suffix forming agent nouns.
Late 16th century (as a verb): probably frequentative, from the base of poke and pocket (suggesting the formation of small purse-like gatherings).
Late 16th century; earliest use found in Thomas North (1535–?1603), translator. From pule + -er.
From puls(ating st)ar, on the pattern of quasar.

Late 16th century (in an earlier sense). From classical Latin pulvīnar couch or cushioned seat of the gods, cushioned seat at a Roman circus, use as noun of neuter of pulvīnāris (adjective) of or belonging to a cushion from pulvīnus cushion, pillow + -āris<br>late 19th century; earliest use found in Proceedings of the Royal Society of London. From pulvinus + -ar.
1970s; earliest use found in New Musical Express. From punk + -ster.

Mid 18th century (in an earlier sense). From classical Latin pūrificāt-, past participial stem of pūrificāre purify + -or; originally after French purificateur. Compare post-classical Latin purificator, Catalan purificador, Spanish purificador, Italian purificatore.
Mid 19th century: from dialect purl ‘upset, overturn’.
Early 19th century; earliest use found in Blackwood's Magazine. From purr + -er.

Late 18th century; earliest use found in Treadway Russell Nash (1725–1811), Church of England clergyman and antiquary. Apparently related to putt, although the nature of the relationship is unexplained.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in John Wilson. From quack + -er.
Latin, from an old form of quaesit- ‘sought’, from the verb quaerere.
Middle English: from Old French quartier, from Latin quartarius ‘fourth part of a measure’, from quartus ‘fourth’, from quattuor ‘four’.

Late Middle English (as a verb in the general sense ‘tremble’): from dialect quave ‘quake, tremble’, probably from an Old English word related to quake. The noun is first recorded (mid 16th century) as a musical term.
Early 16th century: considered to be from German quer ‘oblique, perverse’, but the origin is doubtful.
1920s; earliest use found in Sunday State Journal (Lincoln, Nebraska). From queue + -er.
Middle English: from Old English cwifer ‘nimble, quick’. The initial qu- is probably symbolic of quick movement (as in quaver and quick).
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in The Times. From rabbit + -er.
Mid 19th century. From Radnor, the name of a region in central Powys, east Wales (formerly the county of Radnorshire), where such sheep were originally bred.
Late Middle English. Alteration of Welsh rhaglaw regent, deputy, especially a lord's chief representative in a commot from rhag- pre-, fore- + llaw hand, after -er.
Early 20th century; earliest use found in The Times.

1970s; earliest use found in The Economist. From Ramsar (Persian Rāmsar), the name of a town in northern Iran where the Convention on Wetlands of International Importance Especially as Waterfowl Habitat was signed in 1971.
Early 16th century: from French rapière, from râpe ‘rasp, grater’ (because the perforated hilt resembles a rasp or grater).
Late Middle English: from Latin, literally ‘plunderer’, from rapt- ‘seized’, from the verb rapere.
1930s: from German Raster, literally ‘screen’, from Latin rastrum ‘rake’, from ras- ‘scraped’, from the verb radere.
Early 17th century; earliest use found in Randle Cotgrave (fl. 1587–?1630), lexicographer. From rate + -er.
Middle English: from Old French rasor, from raser ‘shave closely’ (see raze).
Late Middle English: via medieval Latin from Arabic rahj al-ġār ‘arsenic’, literally ‘dust of the cave’.
Early 20th century. From German Realpolitiker from real + Politiker politician, after Realpolitik.
Middle English (first used as a military term): from Old French rere, based on Latin retro ‘back’.
Late 18th century. From reassure + -er. Compare assurer.
Late Middle English; earliest use found in Prefatory Epistle St. Jerome. From post-classical Latin recapitulat-, past participial stem of recapitulare recapitulate + -or.
1920s; earliest use found in U.S. Patents. From recondition + -er.
Late Middle English: from Latin rector ‘ruler’, from rect- ‘ruled’, from the verb regere.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in The Book of Margery Kempe. From Anglo-Norman redemptur Christ, as redeemer (second quarter of the 13th cent. or earlier; compare in same sense Old French redemptor, Middle French redempteur, French rédempteur) and its etymon classical Latin redemptor contractor, person who buys up rights dependent on the outcome of a lawsuit, ransomer, in post-classical Latin also God or Christ as redeemer (Vetus Latina), Trinitarian from redempt-, past participial stem of redimere + -or. Compare Catalan redentor, Spanish redentor, Portuguese redentor, Italian redentore.
Middle English. From reed + -er. Compare later reed.
1930s: perhaps related to Mexican Spanish grifo ‘(smoker of) cannabis’.
Mid 18th century. Probably from Marathi rīp lath used in making a roof or its apparent etymon Telugu rivva, rebba small branch (earlier *rippa, *rimpa), perhaps influenced in form by rafter.
1920s; earliest use found in The Los Angeles Times. From refuel + -er.

Early 16th century; earliest use found in Charter of London. From regard + -er, originally after Anglo-Norman regardour, regardor, regardeor, Anglo-Norman and Middle French regardeur (French regardeur) inspector, controller (both 1170 in Anglo-Norman), spectator, forest officer, and post-classical Latin regardor, reguardor forest officer, regardator forest officer (frequently from 1160 in British sources).
Late Middle English: from Old French regestre or medieval Latin regestrum, registrum, alteration of regestum, singular of late Latin regesta ‘things recorded’, from regerere ‘enter, record’.
Late 15th century; earliest use found in John Lydgate (c1370–c1449), poet and prior of Hatfield Regis. From register + -er. Compare post-classical Latin registerarius.
Late 17th century: from medieval Latin registrarius, from registrum (see register).
Mid 17th century; earliest use found in Edward Waterhouse (1619–1670), heraldic writer. From regret + -er.
Late Middle English: from Old French reguler, from Latin regularis, from regula ‘rule’.
Late Middle English: from Old Norse hreindýri, from hreinn ‘reindeer’ + dýr ‘deer’.

Mid 19th century; earliest use found in John Loudon (1783–1843), landscape gardener and horticultural writer. From the name of Johann Heinrich Riesener, German cabinetmaker and inlay artist, who worked in France, chiefly at the court of Louis XVI.
Late 16th century; earliest use found in John Foxe (?1517–1587), martyrologist. From reject + -er.
Late Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French rejoindre (infinitive used as a noun) (see rejoin).
1940s. Partly from relative + -izer, and partly from relativize + -er.
Mid 19th century. From re- + locator, after relocate.
Mid 16th century; earliest use found in Thomas Stapleton (1535–1598), Roman Catholic theologian. From remain + -er.
Late Middle English. From re- + muster. In later use probably after remuster<br>early 19th century. From re- + muster. Compare remuster.

Late Middle English: from Old French rendre, from an alteration of Latin reddere ‘give back’, from re- ‘back’ + dare ‘give’. The earliest senses were ‘recite’, ‘translate’, and ‘give back’ (hence ‘represent’ and ‘perform’); ‘hand over’ (hence ‘give help’ and ‘submit for consideration’); ‘cause to be’; and ‘melt down’.
Early 17th century; earliest use found in Joshua Sylvester (d. 1618), poet and translator. From re- + offer.
Early 17th century; earliest use found in Randle Cotgrave (fl. 1587–?1630), lexicographer. From repay + -er.
Late 17th century. From repeal + -er. Compare Middle French rappelleur.
1960s; earliest use found in Car and Driver. Blend of replica and car.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in Reginald Pecock (c1392–?1459), bishop of Chichester and religious author. From represent + -er, partly after Middle French representeur person who represents, person who presents, actor, comedian.
Mid 16th century. From represent + -or. Compare earlier representer.
Early 19th century; earliest use found in John Stuart Mill (1806–1873), philosopher, economist, and advocate of women's rights. From restrict + -or.
Mid 17th century; earliest use found in Moderate Intelligencer. From retake + -er.

Late 19th century; earliest use found in Albany Law Journal. From re- + tender, after retender<br>early 17th century; earliest use found in Barnabe Barnes (bap. 1571, d. 1609), poet and playwright. From re- + tender.
Late 17th century (in an earlier sense). From revolution + -er.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in The Wycliffite Bible (early version). From reward + -er. Compare Anglo-Norman rewarder, rewardour someone who rewards or recompenses, and also rewarder, rewardour, variants of regardour.

Early 17th century; earliest use found in Edward Grimeston (fl. 1604–1634), translator. From the name of the Rhineland + -er, after Middle Low German rīnlender or early modern German Reinlender, Rheinlender (German Rheinländer).
Mid 16th century; earliest use found in John Heywood (c1496–c1578), playwright and epigrammatist. From rid + -er.
Mid 18th century; earliest use found in William Ellis (c1700–1758), agriculturist and writer. Partly from ridge + -er, and partly from ridge + -er.
Late Middle English: from Latin, literally ‘stiffness’, from rigere ‘be stiff’.
Early 19th century; earliest use found in James Smith (1775–1839), writer and humorist. Probably from rime + -er, or perhaps a variant of reamer.
Mid 17th century; earliest use found in Henry Hexham (fl. 1601–1650), soldier and author. From rind + -er.
Late 16th century (in an earlier sense). From ripen + -er. In specific medical use in sense 1a after post-classical Latin maturativum maturative.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French, based on Latin riparius, from ripa ‘bank of a river’.
Late 16th century (in an earlier sense). From road + -er.
Mid 19th century: probably derived from a transaltion of Spanish correcamino.
Old English rārian (verb), imitative of a deep prolonged cry, of West Germanic origin; related to German röhren. The noun dates from late Middle English.
1940s; earliest use found in Hearst's International. Either from rod + -er, or shortened from hot rodder.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Hunt's Merchants' Magazine. From the name of the champagne-producing Roederer company of Rheims, France, founded in 1776 by Louis Roederer.

Mid 19th century; earliest use found in John Strang (1795–1863), author and statistician. From German Römer rummer. In later use in quots. mentioning such glasses in a Dutch geographical or cultural context perhaps also partly from Dutch roemer rummer.
Late Middle English; earliest use found in The Wycliffite Bible (later version). From rope + maker. Compare Middle Dutch, Dutch reepmaker (now rare and archaic).

Early 18th century (originally denoting a list of duties and leave for military personnel): from Dutch rooster ‘list’, earlier ‘gridiron’, from roosten ‘to roast’, with reference to its parallel lines.
Early 20th century: formed irregularly from rotator.
Early 20th century: German, from Rottweil, the name of a town in SW Germany.
Middle English: from Middle Low German, Middle Dutch rōver, from rōven ‘rob’; related to reave.

Mid 16th century: from the verb rub + -er. The original sense was ‘an implement (such as a hard brush) used for rubbing and cleaning’. Because an early use of the elastic substance (previously known as caoutchouc) was to rub out pencil marks, rubber gained the sense ‘eraser’ in the late 18th century The sense was subsequently (mid 19th century) generalized to refer to the substance in any form or use, at first often differentiated as India rubber.
Late 19th century; earliest use found in The Titusville Morning Herald.
Old English rōther ‘paddle, oar’, of West Germanic origin; related to Dutch roer, German Ruder, also to the verb row.
1940s; earliest use found in Popular Science Monthly. From rudder + -vator.
Mid 16th century; earliest use found in Acts of Parliament. From ruffle + -er<br>mid 19th century; earliest use found in Annual Reports Commissioner Patents 1867. From ruffle + -er.
Mid 17th century: of Low Dutch origin; related to Dutch roemer; the original meaning is perhaps ‘Roman glass’.
Late Middle English: from Dutch saffloer or German Saflor, via Old French and Italian from Arabic aṣfar ‘yellow’. The spelling has been influenced by saffron and flower.
Mid 18th century: probably a contraction of the noun safeguard.
Late Middle English: from Old French sacre, from Arabic ṣaqr ‘falcon’.
Middle English (in salamander (sense 2)): from Old French salamandre, via Latin from Greek salamandra. Sense 1 dates from the early 17th century.
1930s: named after Shalmaneser, a king of Assyria (2 Kings 17–18).
Mid 17th century: from French salve ‘tray for presenting food to the king’, from Spanish salva ‘sampling of food’, from salvar ‘make safe’.
Late 17th century: from Hindi sābar, from Sanskrit śambara.
Mid 19th century: from Pashto, probably from Persian sang ‘stone’.
From Persian and Urdu sarkār, from sar ‘chief’ + kār agent, doer.
Middle English (denoting a condiment dish): from Old French saussier(e) ‘sauce boat’, probably suggested by late Latin salsarium.
Late Middle English (in the sense ‘to muse, wonder’): of unknown origin. The current sense dates from the mid 17th century.
Late 17th century (in the sense ‘run away’): probably from scamp.
Late Middle English: from Old French escharre, via late Latin from Greek eskhara ‘scab’.
Mid 19th century: probably from Italian scappare ‘to escape’, influenced by rhyming slang Scapa Flow ‘go’.
Middle English (as a verb): probably a variant of shatter.
Early 17th century; earliest use found in Randle Cotgrave (fl. 1587–?1630), lexicographer. From scent + -er.
1950s: from Yiddish schmeck ‘a sniff’ + -er. Compare with smack.
Old English scol(i)ere ‘schoolchild, student’, from late Latin scholaris, from Latin schola (see school).
Early 18th century: perhaps from dialect scun ‘skim along’, influenced by Dutch words beginning with sch-.
Mid 16th century: from French cimeterre or Italian scimitarra, of unknown origin.
Late 17th century: perhaps an error for sooter (with reference to its black plumage).
Middle English (in scrivener (sense 1 of the noun)): shortening of Old French escrivein, from Latin scriba (see scribe). scrivener (sense 2 of the noun) dates from the early 17th century.
Late 18th century: perhaps an alteration of the verb scuttle.
Old English sēar (adjective), sēarian (verb), of Germanic origin.
Late 16th century (in sector (sense 2, sector sense 3)): from late Latin, a technical use of Latin sector ‘cutter’, from sect- ‘cut off’, from the verb secare.

Middle English: secular (sense 1 of the adjective, from Old French seculer, from Latin saecularis, from saeculum ‘generation, age’, used in Christian Latin to mean ‘the world’ (as opposed to the Church); secular (sense 3 of the adjective, secular sense 4 of the adjective, secular sense 5 of the adjective) (early 19th century) from Latin saecularis ‘relating to an age or period’.
1960s; earliest use found in The Listener. From Securicor, the trademark of a private security organization employed in the guarding and safe transport of money, goods, and property.
Early 18th century: from Persian šir o šakar, literally ‘milk and sugar’, (by transference) ‘striped cotton garment’ because seersucker formerly was typically striped.
Mid 18th century: alteration of German Selterser, from ( Nieder)selters (see above).
Early 19th century: from German Semester, from Latin semestris ‘six-monthly’, from sex ‘six’ + mensis ‘month’.
Late 19th century: from German Seminar, from Latin seminarium (see seminary).
Middle English (denoting a member of the ancient Roman senate): from Old French senateur, from Latin senator (see senate).
Late Middle English: from Latin, literally ‘older, older man’, comparative of senex, sen- ‘old man, old’.
Late Old English, from Latin, from septem ‘seven’ (being originally the seventh month of the Roman year).
Late Middle English: from Old French sequestrer or late Latin sequestrare ‘commit for safekeeping’, from Latin sequester ‘trustee’.
1970s. From sero- + -var, after cultivar. Compare pathovar.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French severer, from Latin separare ‘disjoin, divide’.
Old English sceran (originally in the sense ‘cut through with a weapon’), of Germanic origin; related to Dutch and German scheren, from a base meaning ‘divide, shear, shave’.

Middle English (in the sense ‘exempt, cleared’): probably an alteration of dialect shire ‘pure, clear’, from the Germanic base of the verb shine. In the mid 16th century the word was used to describe clear, pure water, and also in sheer (sense 3 of the adjective).
Late 16th century: perhaps an alteration of sheld, an old spelling of shield, + -ure.
Late Old English scymrian, of Germanic origin; related to German schimmern, also to shine. The noun dates from the early 19th century.
Middle English chivere, perhaps an alteration of dialect chavele ‘to chatter’, from Old English ceafl ‘jaw’.
Old English sculdor, of West Germanic origin; related to Dutch schouder and German Schulter.
Old English scūr ‘light fall of rain, hail, etc.’, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch schoer and German Schauer.
Middle English (as a verb): from Middle Dutch schūderen, from a Germanic base meaning ‘shake’.
Mid 19th century: said to be from Scheuster, the name of a lawyer whose behaviour provoked accusations of ‘scheuster’ practices, perhaps reinforced by German Scheisser ‘worthless person’.
Early 17th century; earliest use found in John Lane (fl. 1600–1630). From side + -er.

Late Middle English (in an earlier sense). From classical Latin signifer Zodiac, standard-bearer, use as noun (with reference to the Zodiac short for signifer orbis, signifer circulus, signifer polus) of masculine of signifer carrying or adorned with images, (of the sky) holding the constellations from signum + -fer.
Old English seolfor, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch zilver and German Silber.
Late 16th century (also as a term in anatomy meaning ‘homogeneous’): from French similaire or medieval Latin similaris, from Latin similis ‘like’.
Mid 16th century: of unknown origin; compare with German zimpfer ‘elegant, delicate’.
Middle English (in the sense ‘solitary, single’, also ‘beyond the average’): from Old French singuler, from Latin singularis, from singulus (see single).
Late Middle English (in the sense ‘malicious, underhand’): from Old French sinistre or Latin sinister ‘left’.
Late 18th century (as a noun): from German Sinter; compare with cinder.
Old English, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch zuster and German Schwester, from an Indo-European root shared by Latin soror.
Via Urdu from Persian sitār, from sih ‘three’ + tār ‘string’.
Late 16th century: from obsolete size ‘ration of bread, beer, etc.’ + -ar.
Mid 19th century: shortened form, representing a casual pronunciation.
Late Middle English: of unknown origin.
Mid 19th century: apparently a frequentative of skite.
Middle English: from Old French esclandre, alteration of escandle, from late Latin scandalum (see scandal).
Middle English (as a noun): from Old Norse slátr ‘butcher's meat’; related to slay. The verb dates from the mid 16th century.
Middle English: probably from Low German; compare with slobber.
Middle English: alteration of the dialect verb slidder, frequentative from the base of slide.
Late Middle English: from dialect slive ‘cleave’.
Late Middle English: probably from Middle Dutch slobberen ‘walk through mud’, also ‘feed noisily’, of imitative origin.
Middle English: alteration of Scots and northern English sloom, in the same sense. The -b- was added for ease of pronunciation.
1970s; earliest use found in New York Sunday News Magazine.
Old English smierwan (verb), smeoru ‘ointment, grease’, of Germanic origin; related to German schmieren (verb), Schmer (noun).
Middle English (as a noun in the sense ‘stifling smoke’): from the base of Old English smorian ‘suffocate’.
Late Middle English: related to Dutch smeulen.
Late 16th century: (in sense ‘person or animal that sneaks’): the current sense dates from the late 19th century.
Late Middle English: probably of imitative origin.
Mid 19th century: imitative; compare with dialect snift ‘to snort’.
Early 18th century: later variant of snicker.
Late Middle English: shortening of Old French essorer, based on Latin ex- ‘out of’ + aura ‘breeze’.
From Norse Sudhr-eyjar ‘southern isles’; the islands belonged formerly to Norway.
Late 18th century: named after Daniel C. Solander (1736–82), Swedish botanist.
Late Middle English: from Latin solaris, from sol ‘sun’.
Middle English: from Old French soudure, from the verb souder, from Latin solidare ‘fasten together’, from solidus ‘solid’.
Middle English: from Old French soldier, from soulde ‘(soldier's) pay’, from Latin solidus (see solidus). The verb dates from the early 17th century.
1940s: from so(und) na(vigation and) r(anging), on the pattern of radar.
Middle English (in the sense ‘person who speaks the truth’): see sooth.
Late Middle English: from sorser (from Old French sorcier, based on Latin sors, sort- ‘lot’) + -er.
Early 19th century: from sordid, on the pattern of the pair squalid, squalor.
Old English sūtere, from Latin sutor, from suere ‘sew’.

Mid 19th century. From south + -er<br>Old English. Cognate with Old Frisian sūther, sūder, sūr, Middle Dutch sūder (Dutch zuider), Middle Low German sǖder, Old High German sundar (Middle High German sunder), ultimately showing a formation from the same base as south with different suffixation; compare adverb and noun forms with final -r cited at south [adjective, noun, preposition]<br>early 17th century; earliest use found in Thomas Roe (1581–1644), diplomat. Probably from souther; perhaps compare -er. Compare wester, easter, norther.
Late 18th century: from German spannen ‘draw tight’ + -er.
Middle English: shortening of Old French esparre, or from Old Norse sperra; related to Dutch spar and German Sparren.
Mid 16th century (in the sense ‘splutter while speaking’): frequentative, from a base shared by Dutch, Low German spatten ‘burst, spout’.
Old English spere, of Germanic origin; compare with Dutch speer and German Speer.
Mid 17th century: compare with Old French espeautre, Middle Dutch speauter; related to pewter.
Probably named after the second Earl Spencer (1758–1834), English politician.
Late 16th century: via Latin from Greek sphinktēr, from sphingein ‘bind tight’.
Late Old English spīthra, from spinnan (see spin).
Mid 19th century: from German Spieler ‘player’ (see spiel).
Mid 19th century: apparently a fanciful formation from Sphinx, the name of the yacht first using it, perhaps influenced by spanker.

Late Middle English (in the sense ‘woman who spins’): from the verb spin + -ster; in early use the term was appended to names of women to denote their occupation. The current sense dates from the early 18th century.
Middle English: from Middle Dutch splinter, splenter; related to splint.
Late 17th century: imitative; compare with sputter.
Mid 17th century (as a noun): from Latin, from spondere ‘promise solemnly’. The verb dates from the late 19th century.
Early 19th century: from Afrikaans, from Middle Dutch spor, of Germanic origin.
Late 16th century (as a verb): from Dutch sputteren, of imitative origin.
Early 17th century: from Latin, from squalere ‘be dirty’.
1970s; earliest use found in Dun's Review.
Mid 16th century: from Dutch stadhouder ‘deputy’, from stad ‘place’ + houder ‘holder’, translating medieval Latin locum tenens.
Late Middle English (as a verb): alteration of dialect stacker, from Old Norse stakra, frequentative of staka ‘push, stagger’. The noun dates from the late 16th century.
Late Old English stamerian, of West Germanic origin; related to stumble. The noun dates from the late 18th century.
Old English steorra, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch ster, German Stern, from an Indo-European root shared by Latin stella and Greek astēr.
Late 16th century; earliest use found in Ralph Robinson (1520–1577), translator. From starve + -er.
Via late Latin from Greek statēr, from a base meaning ‘weigh’.
Middle English (in the sense ‘bookseller’): from medieval Latin stationarius ‘tradesman (at a fixed location, i.e. not itinerant)’. Compare with stationary.
Late 19th century: from stationary, on the pattern of rotor.
Old English stīeran, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch sturen and German steuern.
1950s: from stellar (with reference to the fusion processes in stars), on the pattern of generator.
Late Middle English: probably a shortening of Old French estomachier, from estomac (see stomach).
Late Middle English: shortening of Old French estrangier, from Latin extraneus (see strange).
Mid 17th century: from Latin, from stridere ‘to creak’.
1970s: probably a blend of string and trimmer.
Named for two different veterans of earlier wars who shared the surname Stryker.
Late Middle English; earliest use found in John Trevisa (c1342–?1402), translator. From study + -er.
Late Middle English: from Latin, from stupere ‘be amazed or stunned’.
Mid 19th century: named after the village of Sturmer, on the Essex–Suffolk border, where it was first grown.
Late 16th century (as a verb): frequentative of dialect stut, of Germanic origin; related to German stossen ‘strike against’.
Late 16th century (in an earlier sense). From classical Latin sūber cork oak, the bark of this, of unknown origin.
Mid 19th century; earliest use found in Sylvester Judd (1813–1853), novelist. From subordinate + -or.
Late 16th century (in an earlier sense). From substitute + -er.
Early 17th century: from late Latin, from Latin succinere ‘sing to, chime in’, from sub- ‘subordinately’ + canere ‘sing’.
Middle English: from Old French sukere, from Italian zucchero, probably via medieval Latin from Arabic sukkar.
Late Middle English (in the sense ‘member of a retinue’): from Anglo-Norman French seutor, from Latin secutor, from sequi ‘follow’.
Old English sumor, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch zomer, German Sommer, also to Sanskrit samā ‘year’.
Middle English: from Old French sommetier, via late Latin from Greek sagma, sagmat- ‘packsaddle’; compare with summer.
Late Middle English: from Old French superiour, from Latin superior, comparative of superus ‘that is above’, from super ‘above’.
Early 20th century; earliest use found in The Sheboygan Press.
Mid 17th century; earliest use found in Daniel Featley (1582–1645), Church of England clergyman and religious controversialist. From supplement + -er.

Late 16th century; earliest use found in Richard Bancroft (bap. 1544, d. 1610), archbishop of Canterbury. From post-classical Latin supplicator suppliant from classical Latin supplicāt-, past participial stem of supplicāre + -or.
Early 20th century; earliest use found in Collier's Weekly. From either surfboard or surfboard + -er.
Mid 16th century: from sur- ‘in addition’ + rejoinder.
Late Middle English (chiefly in legal use): from Anglo-Norman French (see sur-, render).
Late 16th century: from obsolete Dutch soeteler, from soetelen ‘perform mean duties’.
Early 16th century: apparently a frequentative of the verb swag.
Old English swerian of Germanic origin; related to Dutch zweren, German schwören, also to answer.

Early 16th century (in an earlier sense). Partly from table + -er, and partly from table + -er. In sense 1 probably after classical Latin tabulārius accountant, book-keeper, or similar. In sense 2 after Hellenistic Greek τραπεζίτης money changer (New Testament).
Middle English: from Old French tabour ‘drum’; perhaps related to Persian tabīra ‘drum’. Compare with tambour.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French taillour, literally ‘cutter’, based on late Latin taliare ‘to cut’. The verb dates from the mid 17th century.
Early 17th century (originally as tangara): from Tupi tangará, later refashioned on the pattern of the modern Latin genus name Tanagra.
From Urdu tandūr, from Persian tanūr, based on Arabic tannūr ‘oven’.
1940s; earliest use found in Dunkirk (New York) Evening Observer.
Old English (denoting any wax candle), dissimilated form (by alteration of p- to t-) of Latin papyrus (see papyrus), the pith of which was used for candle wicks.
Old English teru, teoru, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch teer, German Teer, and perhaps ultimately to tree.
Late 18th century: from French, from tarse ‘tarsus’, with reference to the animal's long tarsal bones.
Late Middle English: via medieval Latin from medieval Greek tartaron, of unknown origin.
1970s: from the initial letters of Tom Swift's electric rifle (a fictitious weapon), on the pattern of laser.
The Turkic name of a Tartar tribe.
Old English teran, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch teren and German zehren, from an Indo-European root shared by Greek derein ‘flay’. The noun dates from the early 17th century.
Early 20th century: blend of technical and color.
1920s; earliest use found in The Glasgow Herald. Probably partly from televis- + -or.

Old English temprian ‘bring something into the required condition by mixing it with something else’, from Latin temperare ‘mingle, restrain’. Sense development was probably influenced by Old French temprer ‘to temper, moderate’. The noun originally denoted a proportionate mixture of elements or qualities, also the combination of the four bodily humours, believed in medieval times to be the basis of temperament, hence temper (sense 1 of the noun)( late Middle English). Compare with temperament.
Middle English: from Old French templier, from medieval Latin templarius, from Latin templum (see temple).
Late Middle English: via Old French from medieval Latin, based on tenere ‘to hold’; so named because the tenor part was allotted (and therefore ‘held’) the melody.
Middle English: from medieval Latin tentorium, from tent- ‘stretched’, from the verb tendere.
Late Middle English: from Old French (chien) terrier ‘earth (dog)’, from medieval Latin terrarius, from Latin terra ‘earth’.
Late Middle English: from Old French terrour, from Latin terror, from terrere ‘frighten’.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French testatour, from Latin testator, from the verb testari ‘testify’.
Late Middle English: from Old Norse tjóthr, from a Germanic base meaning ‘fasten’.
Early 17th century: from late Latin tetrametrus, from Greek tetrametros, from tetra- ‘four’ + metron ‘measure’.
German, earlier form of Taler (see dollar).
Mid 17th century: from Greek, literally ‘palm of the hand, sole of the foot’.
Mid 17th century: from French thermomètre or modern Latin thermometrum, from thermo- ‘of heat’ + -metrum ‘measure’.
Old English thunor (noun), thunrian (verb), of Germanic origin; related to Dutch donder and German Donner (noun), from an Indo-European root shared by Latin tonare ‘to thunder’.
1950s: blend of thyratron, denoting a kind of thermionic valve (from Greek thura ‘gate’) and transistor.
Late 19th century: perhaps related to tiddly or tittlebat, a childish form of stickleback.
Middle English: from Old French tigre, from Latin tigris, from Greek.
Old English in the sense ‘a building’, also ‘building material’, of Germanic origin; related to German Zimmer ‘room’, from an Indo-European root meaning ‘build’.
Old English tynder, tyndre, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch tonder and German Zunder.
Middle English (first recorded in Anglo-Latin as a surname): of unknown origin.
1930s: abbreviation of rhyming slang tit for tat.
Late 15th century: from Irish tochra, Scottish Gaelic tochradh.
Old English tōgædere, based on the preposition to + a West Germanic word related to gather. The adjective dates from the 1960s.
Late 18th century; earliest use found in The London Magazine. Representing a regional or colloquial pronunciation (with reduction of the vowel in the final syllable) of tomorrow.
Early 18th century: from Greek tonos (see tone) + -meter.
Old English torr, perhaps of Celtic origin and related to Welsh tor ‘belly’ and Scottish Gaelic tòrr ‘bulging hill’.
Spanish, from torear ‘fight bulls’, from toro ‘bull’.
Late Middle English: from Latin, from torpere ‘be numb or sluggish’.
Mid 17th century: from Old French tort-fesor, from tort ‘wrong’ and fesor ‘doer’.
Late 18th century (in the general sense ‘someone or something that pulls’): from Latin, from tract- ‘pulled’, from the verb trahere.
1980s: from the name of Milton Trager (1908–97), the American doctor who invented the technique.
Middle English: from Old French traitour, from Latin traditor, from tradere ‘hand over’.
Named after the Italian village Termeno.

Late Middle English (as a verb): from French transférer or Latin transferre, from trans- ‘across’ + ferre ‘to bear’. The earliest use of the noun (late 17th century) was as a legal term in the sense ‘conveyance of property’.
1940s: from transconductance, on the pattern of words such as varistor.
Middle English: from Old French tresorier, from tresor (see treasure), influenced by late Latin thesaurarius.
Early 17th century: from Latin tremor, from tremere ‘to tremble’.
Early 17th century: from dialect tricker, from Dutch trekker, from trekken ‘to pull’.
Early 19th century: from French trimestre, from Latin trimestris, from tri- ‘three’ + mensis ‘month’.
Mid 16th century: via Latin from Greek trimetros, from tri- ‘three’ + metron ‘measure’.
Early 18th century: from French trocart, trois-quarts, from trois ‘three’ + carre ‘side, face of an instrument’.
Early 17th century: from French, from Greek trokhantēr, from trekhein ‘to run’.
Old English; earliest use found in Monasteriales Indicia. Originally from post-classical Latin troparium, troperium.
Late 16th century: from an Anglo-Norman French noun use of Old French trover ‘to find’.
From Russian tsarʹ, representing Latin Caesar.
Mid 17th century: from Latin, literally ‘hump, swelling’.
Late 19th century: from late Latin, from turgere ‘to swell’.
Late Middle English: from Old French tutour or Latin tutor, from tueri ‘to watch, guard’.
Late Middle English (as a verb): imitative.
Old English ūder, of West Germanic origin; related to Dutch uier and German Euter.
Late Middle English: from Latin ulcus, ulcer-.
Late 19th century: from Ulster, where it was originally sold.
Early 18th century: from obsolete French umbellifère, from Latin umbella ‘parasol’ + -fer ‘bearing’.
Mid 16th century: from French (terre d')ombre or Italian (terra di) ombra, literally ‘(earth of) shadow’, from Latin umbra ‘shadow’ or Umbra (feminine) ‘Umbrian’.
1960s; earliest use found in Proceedings of the AFIPS Conference. From uni- + processor.
Mid 16th century; earliest use found in Discourse Match Duke of Norfolke & Queene of Scottes. From unite + -er.

Early 17th century; earliest use found in William Warner (d. 1609), poet and lawyer. From post-classical Latin unitor person who unites from classical Latin ūnīt-, past participial stem of ūnīre + -or.
Middle English: from the adjective up + -er.
Early 16th century: from Middle Dutch uproer, from op ‘up’ + roer ‘confusion’, associated with roar.
Late 16th century: from French uretère or modern Latin ureter, from Greek ourētēr, from ourein ‘urinate’.
Early 17th century (in an earlier sense). In sense 1 probably from Middle French, French usager person who has the right to use something from usage + -er.
Late Middle English (denoting a doorkeeper): from Anglo-Norman French usser, from medieval Latin ustiarius, from Latin ostiarius, from ostium ‘door’.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French, from Old French usure, from Latin usura (see usury).
Mid 19th century: from Latin, literally ‘carrier’, from vehere ‘convey’.
Early 18th century: from Latin velaris, from velum (see velum).
Mid 17th century: Latin, from venari ‘to hunt’.
Early 18th century (earlier as fineer): from German furni(e)ren, from Old French fournir ‘furnish’.
Mid 16th century: from Anglo-Norman French, based on Latin viridis ‘green’.
Middle English (in verger (sense 2)): from Anglo-Norman French (see verge).
Early 17th century: from Latin vernaculus ‘domestic, native’ (from verna ‘home-born slave’) + -ar.
Mid 18th century: named after Pierre Vernier (1580–1637), French mathematician.
Late Middle English: from Latin vesper ‘evening (star)’.
1970s; earliest use found in The Daily Telegraph. From vet + -er.
Middle English: via Anglo-Norman French from Old French vicaire, from Latin vicarius ‘substitute’, from vic- ‘change, turn, place’ (compare with vice).
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French victo(u)r or Latin victor, from vincere ‘conquer’.
Middle English: from Old French vyn egre, based on Latin vinum ‘wine’ + acer ‘sour’.
Late Middle English: via Anglo-Latin from Old French vinetier, from medieval Latin vinetarius, from Latin vinetum ‘vineyard’, from vinum ‘wine’.
Early 16th century: from French vipère or Latin vipera, from vivus ‘alive’ + parere ‘bring forth’.
Late 19th century: from late Latin viscosus ‘viscous’ + -meter.
Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French viser, from Old French vis ‘face’, from Latin visus (see visage).
Mid 16th century: via Turkish from Arabic wazīr ‘caliph's chief counsellor’.
Late 16th century (as a noun, with military reference): from French volontaire ‘voluntary’. The change in the ending was due to association with -eer.
Afrikaans, from Dutch voor ‘fore’ + trekken ‘to travel’.
Late Middle English: from an Anglo-Norman French variant of Old French gaufre (see goffer), from Middle Low German wāfel ‘waffle’; compare with waffle.
Middle English (also in the sense ‘solemn pledge’): from Anglo-Norman French wageure, from wager ‘to wage’.
Mid 16th century: from Dutch wagenaar, from wagen (see wagon).
Early 19th century: with reference to a horse race in which the winner, through the absence of competitors, has no need to race but can just walk over the finish line.
Old English wandrian, of West Germanic origin; related to wend and wind.
Late Old English werre, from an Anglo-Norman French variant of Old French guerre, from a Germanic base shared by worse.

Late Middle English; earliest use found in John Lydgate (c1370–c1449), poet and prior of Hatfield Regis. From wardrobe + -er, after Anglo-Norman garderober, gardrober, Anglo-Norman and Middle French garderobier, also Anglo-Norman warderoper.
Late Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French warener, from warenne ‘game park’.

Old English wæter (noun), wæterian (verb), of Germanic origin; related to Dutch water, German Wasser, from an Indo-European root shared by Russian voda (compare with vodka), also by Latin unda ‘wave’ and Greek hudōr ‘water’.
Late 16th century; earliest use found in Archaeologia.
Old English werian, of Germanic origin, from an Indo-European root shared by Latin vestis ‘clothing’.
Old English weder, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch weer and German Wetter, probably also to the noun wind.
1940s: from German, from Weimar in Germany, where the breed was developed.
Middle English (in the sense ‘writhe, wallow’): from Middle Dutch, Middle Low German welteren.
Early 19th century (in sense ‘a heavy blow’): from whack + -er. Sense 2 is a back formation from wacky.
Late 16th century: apparently from white (assimilated to wheat) + arse (assimilated to ear).
Mid 17th century (in the sense ‘to snigger, titter’): imitative.
Early 16th century: from dialect whimp ‘to whimper’, of imitative origin.
Late 17th century: perhaps representing whipsnapper, expressing noise and unimportance.
Late Middle English (originally denoting a bundle of feathers, twigs, etc., used for whisking): from the verb whisk + -er.
Old English hwisprian, of Germanic origin; related to German wispeln, from the imitative base of whistle.
Late Middle English: from white + leather.
Middle English: of Scandinavian origin; compare with Swedish viker ‘willow’; related to vika ‘to bend’.
Early 20th century: abbreviation of German Wienerwurst ‘Vienna sausage’.
Early 18th century: originally applied to containers holding a bushel, gallon, or quart, according to an obsolete system of measurement with standards kept at Winchester (see Winchester).
Old English, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch winter and German Winter, probably also to wet.
Early 20th century: from wise + the suffix -(n)heimer found in surnames such as Oppenheimer.
Late Middle English: apparently a variant of weather, ultimately differentiated for certain senses.
Old English wundor (noun), wundrian (verb), of Germanic origin; related to Dutch wonder and German Wunder, of unknown ultimate origin.
1920s; earliest use found in Petroleum Magazine. From work + over, after to work over.
Named after Rudolf Wurlitzer (1831–1914), the German-born American instrument-maker who founded the manufacturing company.
Late Middle English (as a verb meaning ‘lament, cry out’): alteration of earlier yomer, from Old English geōmrian ‘to lament’, suggested by Middle Dutch jammeren.
Early 19th century: imitative, perhaps suggested by yammer and chatter.
Old English gē(a)r, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch jaar and German Jahr, from an Indo-European root shared by Greek hōra ‘season’.
Mid 16th century: -hammer is perhaps from Old English amore (a kind of bird), possibly conflated with hama ‘feathers’.
Probably from York, suggesting its introduction by Yorkshire players.
Early 16th century (denoting a young nobleman): from Middle Dutch jonckher, from jonc ‘young’ + hēre ‘lord’. Compare with Junker.
Mid 20th century: from German Zeitgeber, from Zeit ‘time’ + Geber ‘giver’.
1950s: named after Clarence M. Zener (1905–93), American physicist.
1950s: from Zimmer Orthopaedic Limited, the name of the manufacturer.
Mid 19th century: from German, from Latin cithara (see cittern).
